1
00:02:09,490 --> 00:02:11,360
Ethan?

2
00:02:28,540 --> 00:02:30,470
Be quiet, Prince.

3
00:02:40,990 --> 00:02:43,520
That's your Uncle Ethan!

4
00:02:56,040 --> 00:02:58,400
Welcome home, Ethan.

5
00:03:14,060 --> 00:03:17,480
Lucy... You ain't much bigger than when I last saw you!

6
00:03:17,660 --> 00:03:21,080
I'm Deborah. There's Lucy over there.

7
00:03:21,300 --> 00:03:23,890
Deborah? Debbie...

8
00:03:25,070 --> 00:03:27,900
-And you're Lucy? -Yeah, I'm Lucy.

9
00:03:28,070 --> 00:03:30,160
I'm mighty glad to see you, Uncle Ethan.

10
00:03:30,340 --> 00:03:32,710
She's got a fella. Kisses him, too!

11
00:03:32,880 --> 00:03:34,570
-Ban... -Shut up.

12
00:03:34,740 --> 00:03:36,610
Go on with Lucy and help with supper.

13
00:03:36,810 --> 00:03:41,340
Deborah, you too! Ban.

14
00:03:41,520 --> 00:03:43,280
I was just gonna ask Uncle Ethan

15
00:03:43,280 --> 00:03:45,040
what he's gonna do with his saber.

16
00:03:45,220 --> 00:03:48,210
Well, I kind of figured to give it to you.

17
00:03:48,390 --> 00:03:51,550
Thanks. Thanks, Uncle Ethan.

18
00:03:54,130 --> 00:03:58,050
-How was California? -California? How should I know?

19
00:03:58,230 --> 00:04:00,390
-Mose Harper told us... -Mose Harper?

20
00:04:00,570 --> 00:04:03,460
Is that old goat still creekin' around?

21
00:04:03,640 --> 00:04:05,970
Why doesn't somebody bury him?

22
00:04:06,140 --> 00:04:08,800
No, I ain't been to California.

23
00:04:08,980 --> 00:04:10,870
I don't intend to go either.

24
00:04:11,050 --> 00:04:13,410
Supper will be ready as soon as you wash up.

25
00:04:13,580 --> 00:04:16,470
Let me take your coat. Ethan.

26
00:04:26,300 --> 00:04:28,460
Welcome home, Ethan.

27
00:04:30,070 --> 00:04:31,930
Thanks, Aaron.

28
00:04:45,110 --> 00:04:46,810
Marty, it's Uncle Ethan!

29
00:04:47,380 --> 00:04:49,750
Debbie, sit down.

30
00:04:52,150 --> 00:04:56,250
Good evening, Uncle Ethan. Welcome home, sir.

31
00:04:57,030 --> 00:05:00,450
It's Martin. Martin Pawley.

32
00:05:01,460 --> 00:05:04,390
I'm sorry for bein' late, Aunt Martha.

33
00:05:14,480 --> 00:05:17,870
A fella could mistake you for a half-breed.

34
00:05:18,050 --> 00:05:20,440
Not quite, I'm an eighth Cherokee

35
00:05:20,440 --> 00:05:21,940
and the rest Welsh and English.

36
00:05:22,520 --> 00:05:25,210
-Least that's what they tell me. -Go on, son.

37
00:05:25,420 --> 00:05:26,760
It was Ethan who found you

38
00:05:26,760 --> 00:05:28,280
squallin' under a sage clump...

39
00:05:28,460 --> 00:05:30,320
...after your folks had been massacred.

40
00:05:30,490 --> 00:05:34,620
It just happened to be me. No need to make more of it.

41
00:05:40,340 --> 00:05:41,530
Thank you, Lucy.

42
00:06:05,160 --> 00:06:07,150
Good night, Aunt Martha.

43
00:06:08,700 --> 00:06:10,030
Good night, Martin.

44
00:06:10,200 --> 00:06:12,860
-Uncle Aaron. -Good night, Martin.

45
00:06:13,270 --> 00:06:15,830
-Good night, Uncle Ethan. -Good night.

46
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:17,670
Come ben.

47
00:06:18,110 --> 00:06:19,700
Good night, Ma. 'Night, Pa.

48
00:06:19,880 --> 00:06:22,040
Uncle Ethan, will you tell us about the war?

49
00:06:22,210 --> 00:06:24,240
The war ended three years ago, boy.

50
00:06:24,410 --> 00:06:27,180
It did? So why didn't you come home before now?

51
00:06:27,350 --> 00:06:31,670
Ben, go on with Martin. March!

52
00:06:34,420 --> 00:06:37,620
Uncle Ethan, Lucy's wearing the gold locket

53
00:06:37,790 --> 00:06:40,350
you gave her when she was a little girl.

54
00:06:40,530 --> 00:06:42,180
She doesn't wear it much on account of

55
00:06:42,180 --> 00:06:43,420
it makes her neck green.

56
00:06:43,600 --> 00:06:46,690
-Deborah! -Well, it does!

57
00:06:46,870 --> 00:06:49,700
But, I wouldn't care if you gave me a gold locket...

58
00:06:49,870 --> 00:06:51,860
...if it made my neck green or not.

59
00:06:52,040 --> 00:06:53,870
-A gold locket! -Debbie!

60
00:06:54,040 --> 00:06:57,030
Lucy, where are my saddlebags?

61
00:07:15,300 --> 00:07:18,290
Look at my gold locket!

62
00:07:18,470 --> 00:07:20,890
Oh, it is pretty.

63
00:07:21,400 --> 00:07:25,260
-Ethan, I think she's too young... -Oh, let her have it.

64
00:07:25,440 --> 00:07:28,470
-It doesn't amount to much. -To bed, young lady!

65
00:07:28,640 --> 00:07:30,510
-Yes, Daddy. -Thank you, Uncle Ethan

66
00:07:30,680 --> 00:07:33,170
To the bed

67
00:07:37,290 --> 00:07:40,980
I passed the Todd place comin' in. What happened?

68
00:07:41,360 --> 00:07:44,350
He gave up, quit, went back to chopping cotton.

69
00:07:44,560 --> 00:07:46,550
So did the Jamisons.

70
00:07:47,460 --> 00:07:49,660
Without Martha...

71
00:07:51,430 --> 00:07:53,820
She just wouldn't let a man quit.

72
00:07:54,000 --> 00:07:57,300
Ethan, I saw it in you before the war.

73
00:07:57,470 --> 00:07:59,030
You wanted to clear out.

74
00:07:59,210 --> 00:08:01,470
You stayed beyond any real reason. Why?

75
00:08:01,880 --> 00:08:05,340
-Aaron, please... -Are you asking me to clear out now?

76
00:08:05,510 --> 00:08:06,850
You're my brother, Ethan.

77
00:08:06,850 --> 00:08:07,940
You're welcome to stay here as long as

78
00:08:08,120 --> 00:08:10,710
you have a mind to. Ain't that right, Martha?

79
00:08:10,890 --> 00:08:14,190
-Of course, it is. -I expect to pay my way.

80
00:08:14,360 --> 00:08:17,120
There are 60 double eagles in there.

81
00:08:17,290 --> 00:08:21,290
And twice that much here. Yankee dollars.

82
00:08:23,400 --> 00:08:25,530
That's fresh minted.

83
00:08:25,700 --> 00:08:29,090
-There ain't a mark on it. -So?

84
00:09:21,660 --> 00:09:25,110
Aaron, Open up! It's Sam Clayton.

85
00:09:25,290 --> 00:09:27,180
Aaron!

86
00:09:34,770 --> 00:09:36,860
-Reverend, come on in! -Good morning, Aaron

87
00:09:37,040 --> 00:09:39,770
-Good morning, Sister Edwards. -Good morning!

88
00:09:39,940 --> 00:09:42,270
-Good morning, Ben and Debbie. -Good morning, Charlie.

89
00:09:42,440 --> 00:09:44,570
-What is it, Reverend? -Lars just said

90
00:09:44,750 --> 00:09:45,830
somebody busted into his corral last night

91
00:09:45,830 --> 00:09:47,640
and ran off with his best cows.

92
00:09:47,820 --> 00:09:50,380
Yeah, next time I'll raise pigs, by golly!

93
00:09:50,550 --> 00:09:54,040
You never hear of anyone runnin' off pigs, I bet you!

94
00:09:54,220 --> 00:09:55,600
Bumblebees, by golly!

95
00:09:55,600 --> 00:09:57,950
Coffee'll be just fine, Sister. Good morning, Lucy.

96
00:09:58,130 --> 00:10:00,550
-Good morning, Reverend. -Debbie, you been baptized yet?

97
00:10:00,730 --> 00:10:02,420
-No, I haven't. -Aaron, get Martin.

98
00:10:02,600 --> 00:10:05,790
-Martin! -Thank you, sister.

99
00:10:06,230 --> 00:10:09,470
I can sure use that coffee. Pass the sugar, son.

100
00:10:10,110 --> 00:10:12,340
Wait a minute, Sister.

101
00:10:12,510 --> 00:10:16,140
I didn't get any coffee yet. Just hold on a second, Sister.

102
00:10:16,310 --> 00:10:19,580
I'm sure fond of them doughnuts.

103
00:10:19,750 --> 00:10:22,580
Aaron! Martin! Come on up here.

104
00:10:22,750 --> 00:10:25,170
Come on. Raise your right hand. Martin?

105
00:10:25,350 --> 00:10:27,910
-Yes, sir. -Raise your right hand.

106
00:10:28,090 --> 00:10:29,570
You're hereby voluntary privates

107
00:10:29,570 --> 00:10:32,120
in Company A of the Texas Rangers...

108
00:10:32,290 --> 00:10:33,690
...and you will faithfully discharge...

109
00:10:33,690 --> 00:10:34,520
Can I go with you?

110
00:10:34,730 --> 00:10:37,250
Quiet!

111
00:10:37,430 --> 00:10:39,420
-Where was I? -Faithfully fulfill.

112
00:10:39,600 --> 00:10:41,870
-You will faithfully discharge your... -Mrs. Edwards?

113
00:10:42,040 --> 00:10:44,130
Shut up!

114
00:10:44,510 --> 00:10:47,700
You will faithfully discharge your duties, as such...

115
00:10:47,880 --> 00:10:50,830
...without a recompense or monetary consideration.

116
00:10:51,010 --> 00:10:53,670
Amen. That means no pay. Better get a shirt on, Aaron.

117
00:10:53,850 --> 00:10:55,840
I ain't goin' volunteering till I've had my coffee.

118
00:10:56,020 --> 00:10:58,440
-Drink your own. Reverend. -Just call me "Captain."

119
00:10:58,620 --> 00:11:02,110
Captain. The Reverend Samuel Johnson Clayton!

120
00:11:02,290 --> 00:11:04,350
Mighty impressive.

121
00:11:04,530 --> 00:11:08,120
Well...the "Prodigal Brother"!

122
00:11:08,300 --> 00:11:09,950
When did you get back?

123
00:11:09,950 --> 00:11:12,220
I ain't seen you since the surrender.

124
00:11:12,400 --> 00:11:15,030
Come to think of it, I didn't see you at the surrender.

125
00:11:15,200 --> 00:11:17,410
I don't believe in surrenders.

126
00:11:17,410 --> 00:11:19,830
I still got my saber, Reverend.

127
00:11:20,010 --> 00:11:22,500
Didn't turn it into no plowshare neither.

128
00:11:22,710 --> 00:11:24,870
The Indians did it, Mrs. Edwards.

129
00:11:25,050 --> 00:11:28,680
Caddos or Kiowas. Old Mose knows. Yes, sir.

130
00:11:28,850 --> 00:11:30,980
-Oh, shut up, Mose. -Thank you.

131
00:11:31,150 --> 00:11:33,520
-My cow is... -Ethan, I'm countin' on you

132
00:11:33,690 --> 00:11:35,520
to look after things while I'm gone.

133
00:11:35,690 --> 00:11:37,420
-You're not goin'. -He is going.

134
00:11:37,590 --> 00:11:40,080
-I already swore him in. -Swear him out!

135
00:11:40,300 --> 00:11:42,350
-I'll go with you. -I don't think I should...

136
00:11:42,530 --> 00:11:45,860
Stay close, Aaron. It might be, this is rustlers.

137
00:11:46,300 --> 00:11:49,160
Might be this dodderin' ol' idiot ain't so far wrong.

138
00:11:49,340 --> 00:11:50,670
Could be Comanches.

139
00:11:50,840 --> 00:11:54,000
Kind words, Ethan. Thank you kindly.

140
00:11:54,340 --> 00:11:55,830
Children, go with Lucy.

141
00:11:56,010 --> 00:11:57,340
-Oh, Mom... -Ben!

142
00:11:57,510 --> 00:11:59,400
Comanches.

143
00:12:00,320 --> 00:12:02,270
All right. I'll swear you in.

144
00:12:02,450 --> 00:12:04,610
No need to. It wouldn't be legal anyway.

145
00:12:04,820 --> 00:12:09,050
Why not? You wanted for a crime, Ethan?

146
00:12:09,590 --> 00:12:13,020
-Coffee, Ethan. -Thank you, Martha.

147
00:12:13,190 --> 00:12:17,690
Are you asking me as a captain or a preacher, Sam?

148
00:12:17,870 --> 00:12:18,450
I'm asking you

149
00:12:18,450 --> 00:12:20,790
as a ranger of the sovereign state of Texas.

150
00:12:20,970 --> 00:12:24,130
-You got a warrant? -You fit a lot of descriptions.

151
00:12:24,910 --> 00:12:28,470
I figure a man's only good for one oath at a time.

152
00:12:28,640 --> 00:12:32,140
I took mine to the Confederate States of America.

153
00:12:32,610 --> 00:12:35,110
So did you, Sam.

154
00:12:35,250 --> 00:12:37,620
Stay close, Aaron.

155
00:12:37,890 --> 00:12:40,450
Thank you, Mrs. Edwards. We have to be going.

156
00:12:40,620 --> 00:12:42,580
Thank you, Mrs. Edwards.

157
00:12:42,760 --> 00:12:47,490
Grateful to the hospitality of your rocking chair, ma'am.

158
00:12:56,610 --> 00:13:00,500
Brad and Lucy, Lucy and Brad

159
00:13:00,680 --> 00:13:04,240
Debbie and Ben Edwards, I'm gonna tell Ma on you!

160
00:14:37,910 --> 00:14:41,260
Brad, right here.

161
00:14:49,380 --> 00:14:51,380
Uncle Ethan!

162
00:14:53,520 --> 00:14:56,010
Somethin' mighty fishy about this trail, Uncle Ethan.

163
00:14:56,190 --> 00:14:59,220
Don't call me "Uncle." I ain't your uncle.

164
00:14:59,390 --> 00:15:00,730
Yes, sir.

165
00:15:00,900 --> 00:15:03,690
No need to call me "sir" either.

166
00:15:03,870 --> 00:15:06,700
Nor "grandpa," nor "Methuselah."

167
00:15:06,870 --> 00:15:09,130
I can whip you to a frazzle.

168
00:15:09,300 --> 00:15:12,430
-What do you want me to call you? -My name is Ethan.

169
00:15:12,610 --> 00:15:15,870
Now what's so mighty fishy about this trail?

170
00:15:16,040 --> 00:15:19,280
-Well, first... -Look! Look! Brad!

171
00:15:34,280 --> 00:15:34,980
Pa!

172
00:15:36,970 --> 00:15:38,800
Reverend!

173
00:15:40,400 --> 00:15:42,130
Look.

174
00:15:56,650 --> 00:15:59,640
Caddos or Kiowas, huh?

175
00:16:01,420 --> 00:16:04,310
Ain't but one tribe uses a lance like that.

176
00:16:04,490 --> 00:16:07,620
Hey, Pa, your prize bull.

177
00:16:07,800 --> 00:16:09,130
Killed every one of them!

178
00:16:09,800 --> 00:16:13,100
And not for food either. Why'd they do a thing like that?

179
00:16:13,270 --> 00:16:16,120
Stealing the cattle was just to pull us out.

180
00:16:16,300 --> 00:16:18,000
This is a murder raid.

181
00:16:18,170 --> 00:16:21,060
Shapes up to burn down either your place,

182
00:16:21,060 --> 00:16:22,670
or my brother's.

183
00:16:22,840 --> 00:16:25,470
Mama! Laurie!

184
00:16:25,650 --> 00:16:28,340
Oh, please, God! Please, no!

185
00:16:28,520 --> 00:16:31,080
Brad! Brad! Son!

186
00:16:34,320 --> 00:16:36,350
Jorgensen's place is the closest, Ethan.

187
00:16:36,520 --> 00:16:39,530
If they're not there, we'll come straight on to you.

188
00:16:39,530 --> 00:16:40,650
Come on, Charlie.

189
00:16:40,830 --> 00:16:42,660
You do that.

190
00:16:42,830 --> 00:16:44,990
Well, are you coming, or ain't you?

191
00:16:45,170 --> 00:16:48,400
That farm's 40 miles from here, boy.

192
00:16:48,400 --> 00:16:50,830
And these horses need rest and grain.

193
00:17:00,850 --> 00:17:05,240
Ain't Caddos. Ain't Kiowas. Comanche.

194
00:17:13,930 --> 00:17:18,820
-Break out the grain. -Yes, sir. Yes, sir.

195
00:17:45,730 --> 00:17:47,650
Quiet, boy.

196
00:18:16,060 --> 00:18:18,950
I'll see if I can shoot a couple of sage hens

197
00:18:18,950 --> 00:18:19,910
for supper.

198
00:18:20,090 --> 00:18:22,690
Yes, you do that, Aaron.

199
00:18:28,800 --> 00:18:30,930
Ma, the days are getting shorter.

200
00:18:30,930 --> 00:18:33,300
Lucy, we don't need a lamp yet.

201
00:18:33,740 --> 00:18:36,570
Let's just enjoy the dusk.

202
00:18:46,420 --> 00:18:48,790
It's all right, Ma, I've been watching.

203
00:18:48,960 --> 00:18:50,690
-Only... -What, Ben?

204
00:18:50,860 --> 00:18:54,160
I wish Uncle Ethan was here. Don't you, Ma?

205
00:19:07,040 --> 00:19:10,830
Close that shutter, Ben, like a good boy.

206
00:19:22,990 --> 00:19:25,650
-Ma...I can't... -Lucy!

207
00:19:47,080 --> 00:19:48,970
We're gonna play the "sleep-out" game. Remember?

208
00:19:49,150 --> 00:19:51,140
Where you hide out with Grandma?

209
00:19:51,320 --> 00:19:54,210
-Where she is buried? -And you creep along the ditch

210
00:19:54,390 --> 00:19:57,480
-very quietly, like... -Like a little mouse.

211
00:19:57,660 --> 00:19:59,720
Hurry up! Martha! The moon's fixin' to rise!

212
00:19:59,890 --> 00:20:02,150
You won't make a sound or come back,

213
00:20:02,150 --> 00:20:03,560
no matter what you hear!

214
00:20:03,730 --> 00:20:07,360
-Promise? -I promise.

215
00:20:07,540 --> 00:20:09,830
Wait. Can't I have my doll?

216
00:20:10,000 --> 00:20:13,000
-There's no time. There's no time. -Here she is, baby.

217
00:20:16,110 --> 00:20:17,440
Here.

218
00:20:18,450 --> 00:20:20,710
Now, down low. Run!

219
00:20:20,880 --> 00:20:22,800
Baby!

220
00:20:33,830 --> 00:20:35,890
Chris, go back. Go back, Chris! Go back!

221
00:20:36,060 --> 00:20:39,360
Go back, Chris!

222
00:20:39,530 --> 00:20:44,100
Chris, go back.

223
00:21:13,900 --> 00:21:15,860
Uncle Ethan!

224
00:21:16,800 --> 00:21:18,800
Uncle Ethan!

225
00:21:19,310 --> 00:21:20,930
Wait a minute, Uncle Ethan.

226
00:21:21,110 --> 00:21:23,630
Next time you'll mind your Uncle Ethan.

227
00:21:23,810 --> 00:21:24,600
Thank you kindly...

228
00:21:24,600 --> 00:21:26,800
Wait, Mose! We can ride double, Mose!

229
00:21:26,980 --> 00:21:29,580
Mose! Please!

230
00:21:32,250 --> 00:21:34,120
Mose!

231
00:22:07,420 --> 00:22:10,850
Martha! Martha!

232
00:22:50,160 --> 00:22:52,090
Aunt Martha!

233
00:22:53,000 --> 00:22:54,330
Aunt Martha!

234
00:22:57,070 --> 00:22:59,270
-Let me in. -Don't go in there, boy.

235
00:22:59,470 --> 00:23:02,970
-I know she's in there! Let me in. -Don't go in there.

236
00:23:05,550 --> 00:23:08,380
Don't let him look in there, Mose.

237
00:23:08,550 --> 00:23:10,040
It won't do him any good.

238
00:23:14,420 --> 00:23:17,020
Lucy! Debbie!

239
00:23:54,660 --> 00:23:57,320
-Put an "Amen" to it! -I'm not finished yet.

240
00:23:57,530 --> 00:24:00,060
There's no more time for praying. Amen!

241
00:24:00,230 --> 00:24:02,230
Brad! Martin!

242
00:24:02,670 --> 00:24:04,330
Amen.

243
00:24:24,660 --> 00:24:28,180
Those girls mean as much to me

244
00:24:28,180 --> 00:24:29,590
as though they were my own.

245
00:24:29,760 --> 00:24:31,220
Maybe you don't know that my Brad

246
00:24:31,220 --> 00:24:33,500
has been keeping company with Lucy.

247
00:24:33,670 --> 00:24:36,330
I'd be obliged if you'd come to the point, ma'am.

248
00:24:36,500 --> 00:24:38,700
It's just that I know Martha would want you...

249
00:24:38,870 --> 00:24:41,260
...to take care of her boys, as well as her girls.

250
00:24:41,440 --> 00:24:43,900
If the girls are dead,

251
00:24:43,900 --> 00:24:46,610
don't let the boys waste their lives in vengeance.

252
00:24:46,950 --> 00:24:49,310
Promise me, Ethan!

253
00:24:49,480 --> 00:24:51,850
Come on, if you're going with us!

254
00:25:18,150 --> 00:25:21,480
Captain!

255
00:25:44,340 --> 00:25:48,160
Another one, huh? Give me a hand, Charlie.

256
00:25:57,850 --> 00:26:00,410
This one came a long way before he died, Captain.

257
00:26:00,590 --> 00:26:03,200
Well, Ethan, there's another one

258
00:26:03,210 --> 00:26:04,250
you can score up for your brother.

259
00:26:06,730 --> 00:26:08,790
-I don't like it! -What don't you like?

260
00:26:08,960 --> 00:26:11,520
Indians on a raid generally hide their dead.

261
00:26:11,700 --> 00:26:14,090
If they don't care anything about us knowin'...

262
00:26:14,270 --> 00:26:16,290
...it only spells one thing

263
00:26:16,470 --> 00:26:18,620
They ain't afraid of us following,

264
00:26:18,620 --> 00:26:20,240
or of us catchin' up with them either.

265
00:26:20,410 --> 00:26:24,200
You can back out any time you want, Nesby.

266
00:26:24,910 --> 00:26:26,970
Ethan, I didn't say that!

267
00:26:27,180 --> 00:26:28,480
I didn't say such!

268
00:26:28,680 --> 00:26:31,280
Easy, Nesby, easy.

269
00:26:35,190 --> 00:26:36,950
Jorgensen!

270
00:26:37,190 --> 00:26:40,120
Why don't you finish the job?

271
00:26:48,570 --> 00:26:52,230
-What good did that do you? -By what you preach, none.

272
00:26:52,410 --> 00:26:54,240
But what that Comanche believes...

273
00:26:54,410 --> 00:26:56,900
...ain't got no eyes, he can't enter the Spirit Land.

274
00:26:57,080 --> 00:26:59,440
Has to wander forever between the winds.

275
00:26:59,610 --> 00:27:03,610
You get it, Reverend. Come on, Blankethead!

276
00:27:09,620 --> 00:27:12,010
All right, boys. Let's mount up.

277
00:27:23,270 --> 00:27:26,870
They're camped by the river, about 20 miles from here.

278
00:27:28,610 --> 00:27:32,050
We'll wait till dark, then circle out

279
00:27:32,050 --> 00:27:34,240
so we can jump 'em before daylight.

280
00:27:34,880 --> 00:27:37,370
You're sure you want to jump 'em, Ethan?

281
00:27:39,990 --> 00:27:41,850
That's what we came for, ain't it?

282
00:27:42,020 --> 00:27:46,050
I thought we were tryin' to get them girls out...alive.

283
00:27:46,260 --> 00:27:47,460
If we jump them Comanches,

284
00:27:47,460 --> 00:27:49,180
they'll kill 'em. You know that.

285
00:27:49,360 --> 00:27:52,330
What are we doing then, Reverend?

286
00:27:52,330 --> 00:27:54,150
What are we supposed to do, Ethan?

287
00:27:54,340 --> 00:27:56,200
Well, what I had in mind was

288
00:27:56,200 --> 00:27:59,190
maybe runnin' off their pony herd.

289
00:27:59,370 --> 00:28:01,900
A Comanche on foot is more apt to be willin' to listen.

290
00:28:02,080 --> 00:28:04,170
I think the Reverend's right. Don't you?

291
00:28:04,350 --> 00:28:06,840
You think the Reverend's...

292
00:28:07,010 --> 00:28:09,280
What does a quarter-breed Cherokee

293
00:28:09,280 --> 00:28:10,910
know about the old Comanche trick...

294
00:28:11,090 --> 00:28:15,880
...of sleepin' with his best pony tied right by his side?

295
00:28:16,060 --> 00:28:17,610
You've got about as much chance of

296
00:28:17,610 --> 00:28:19,480
stampeding that herd as...

297
00:28:19,660 --> 00:28:21,990
As you have of finding them girls alive

298
00:28:22,000 --> 00:28:23,550
by raidin' into 'em!

299
00:28:23,730 --> 00:28:27,330
I say we do it my way. And that's an order!

300
00:28:27,500 --> 00:28:29,160
Yes, sir.

301
00:28:29,340 --> 00:28:30,890
But if you're wrong...

302
00:28:32,040 --> 00:28:34,560
...don't ever give me another!

303
00:29:15,950 --> 00:29:20,110
-Well, they were here. -Sure. They were here.

304
00:29:20,290 --> 00:29:24,210
And now they're out there, waiting to jump us.

305
00:29:24,390 --> 00:29:26,620
Any more orders, "Captain"?

306
00:29:26,790 --> 00:29:30,060
Yes. We'll keep on going.

307
00:29:40,010 --> 00:29:41,800
Well?

308
00:29:41,980 --> 00:29:44,240
You want to quit, Ethan?

309
00:29:44,410 --> 00:29:47,010
That'll be the day!

310
00:29:47,480 --> 00:29:49,610
-Horses! -Horses!

311
00:30:01,500 --> 00:30:03,660
Keep on going.

312
00:30:47,540 --> 00:30:50,810
Keep moving! Keep moving!

313
00:31:24,580 --> 00:31:26,110
Well, Reverend,

314
00:31:26,110 --> 00:31:28,870
it looks like you got yourself surrounded.

315
00:31:29,050 --> 00:31:32,080
Yeah, and I figure I can get myself un-surrounded.

316
00:31:32,250 --> 00:31:34,620
Mose, how far is the river?

317
00:31:35,720 --> 00:31:39,850
I've been baptized, Reverend. I've been baptized.

318
00:31:40,030 --> 00:31:43,720
-Shut up, you fool. -Thank you, kindly. Thank you.

319
00:31:43,900 --> 00:31:46,390
You'd better get yourself set for another one...

320
00:31:46,570 --> 00:31:49,520
...because when I holler,

321
00:31:49,520 --> 00:31:52,100
I want you to move out in a hurry!

322
00:31:56,280 --> 00:31:58,400
Let's go!

323
00:32:35,050 --> 00:32:37,410
-Take it easy, Nesby. -You'll be all right, Nesby.

324
00:32:37,580 --> 00:32:40,940
-I'm gonna tell 'em, -Ethan. Let's tell 'em!

325
00:32:41,120 --> 00:32:42,950
well, tell them.

326
00:32:44,420 --> 00:32:46,790
-Take it easy, Nesby. -You'll be all right, Nesby.

327
00:32:47,760 --> 00:32:49,960
Come on!

328
00:33:15,820 --> 00:33:17,380
Here.

329
00:33:17,720 --> 00:33:20,020
Here is my Bible. Hold it.

330
00:33:20,190 --> 00:33:22,580
It'll make you feel good.

331
00:33:23,660 --> 00:33:25,890
Thank you, Reverend. Thank you very kindly.

332
00:33:30,470 --> 00:33:33,800
Do you think they'll charge us?

333
00:33:34,170 --> 00:33:36,510
-Are you asking me? -I am.

334
00:33:36,680 --> 00:33:38,300
Well, thank you.

335
00:33:38,650 --> 00:33:41,310
Yep. The Death Song.

336
00:33:41,480 --> 00:33:44,610
The War Chief. He's got to, to save face.

337
00:33:45,390 --> 00:33:49,240
Yes, sir. He'll be right in your lap in a minute, sonny.

338
00:33:51,160 --> 00:33:53,000
For that which we're about to receive,

339
00:33:53,000 --> 00:33:55,190
we thank Thee, O Lord.

340
00:34:34,870 --> 00:34:37,260
You got him, Marty!

341
00:34:52,390 --> 00:34:55,080
Hallelujah!

342
00:34:55,920 --> 00:34:58,120
Dang! Blast it!

343
00:34:58,290 --> 00:35:00,720
Watch it, it's loaded!

344
00:35:30,960 --> 00:35:34,590
No, Ethan. Leave them to carry off their hurt and dead.

345
00:35:34,760 --> 00:35:37,150
Well, Reverend, that does it!

346
00:35:37,330 --> 00:35:40,100
From now on, you stay out of this, all of you!

347
00:35:40,270 --> 00:35:42,160
I don't want you with me.

348
00:35:42,340 --> 00:35:45,230
I don't need you for what I've gotta do!

349
00:35:55,980 --> 00:35:57,710
Well, Edwards, I...

350
00:35:57,880 --> 00:36:01,310
I guess you're right. We gotta get Nesby back.

351
00:36:01,490 --> 00:36:03,550
This is a job for a whole company of rangers...

352
00:36:03,760 --> 00:36:06,390
...or it's a job for one or two men.

353
00:36:06,560 --> 00:36:09,830
Right now, we're too many and not enough.

354
00:36:10,000 --> 00:36:12,800
Me, I'm going on alone.

355
00:36:13,830 --> 00:36:17,190
-Any objections? -Good luck.

356
00:36:19,140 --> 00:36:20,510
There's only one way

357
00:36:20,510 --> 00:36:22,870
you can stop me from looking for Lucy, mister...

358
00:36:23,040 --> 00:36:25,070
...and that's kill me!

359
00:36:25,280 --> 00:36:27,970
That's the way I feel, Uncle Ethan.

360
00:36:28,520 --> 00:36:30,880
Ethan. Sir.

361
00:36:31,050 --> 00:36:34,250
All right. But I'm giving the orders, you hear?

362
00:36:34,420 --> 00:36:36,220
I'm givin' the orders...

363
00:36:36,390 --> 00:36:37,980
...and you'll follow 'em

364
00:36:37,980 --> 00:36:39,420
or we're splittin' up right here and now.

365
00:36:39,590 --> 00:36:41,480
Sure, Ethan.

366
00:36:41,660 --> 00:36:44,430
There's just one reason we're here, ain't it?

367
00:36:44,440 --> 00:36:46,420
It's to find Debbie and Lucy.

368
00:36:50,500 --> 00:36:53,000
If they're still alive.

369
00:36:57,410 --> 00:36:59,210
Mount up.

370
00:37:25,110 --> 00:37:27,870
They gotta stop sometime.

371
00:37:28,040 --> 00:37:30,930
If they're human men at all, they gotta stop!

372
00:37:31,110 --> 00:37:34,870
No, a human rides a horse until it dies,

373
00:37:34,870 --> 00:37:36,540
then he goes on afoot.

374
00:37:36,720 --> 00:37:39,970
A Comanche comes along, gets that horse up,

375
00:37:39,970 --> 00:37:42,140
rides him 20 more miles...

376
00:37:42,360 --> 00:37:44,450
...and then he eats him.

377
00:37:44,720 --> 00:37:46,820
Easy on that!

378
00:37:46,990 --> 00:37:48,650
Sorry.

379
00:37:49,300 --> 00:37:51,820
We don't even know if Debbie and Lucy are in this bunch.

380
00:37:52,000 --> 00:37:54,490
-Maybe they split up. -They're with 'em, all right.

381
00:37:54,670 --> 00:37:57,630
-If they're still alive. -You've said that enough!

382
00:37:57,800 --> 00:38:00,970
Maybe Lucy's dead. Maybe they're both dead.

383
00:38:01,140 --> 00:38:02,450
But, if I hear that from you again,

384
00:38:02,450 --> 00:38:04,470
I'll fight you, Mr. Edwards!

385
00:38:04,640 --> 00:38:07,070
That'll be the day!

386
00:38:12,620 --> 00:38:14,480
Spread out!

387
00:38:23,660 --> 00:38:25,960
Found a main trail, but...

388
00:38:26,130 --> 00:38:28,550
...four of them cut out here and

389
00:38:28,550 --> 00:38:30,460
rode on up through that pass.

390
00:38:30,640 --> 00:38:32,940
How come they'd do that, Ethan?

391
00:38:33,410 --> 00:38:36,470
I'll take a look. Keep after the others.

392
00:38:36,640 --> 00:38:39,250
If you want us to fire...

393
00:38:39,250 --> 00:38:41,540
No, nor build bonfires, nor beat drums.

394
00:38:41,720 --> 00:38:44,010
I'll meet you on the far side.

395
00:38:44,990 --> 00:38:46,780
Move!

396
00:39:23,020 --> 00:39:25,180
Do you want some water, Ethan?

397
00:39:38,210 --> 00:39:40,090
The trail leads over there.

398
00:39:40,340 --> 00:39:42,570
Why'd they break off?

399
00:39:44,410 --> 00:39:47,110
Was there water in that canyon?

400
00:39:49,880 --> 00:39:51,210
No water.

401
00:39:52,350 --> 00:39:53,790
Are you all right, Ethan?

402
00:39:54,520 --> 00:39:56,390
I'm all right.

403
00:39:59,930 --> 00:40:01,420
Hei

404
00:40:01,700 --> 00:40:05,260
What happened to your coat? Did you lose it?

405
00:40:05,900 --> 00:40:07,760
I must have.

406
00:40:08,200 --> 00:40:10,620
But I'm not going back for it!

407
00:40:29,420 --> 00:40:30,950
I found 'em!

408
00:40:31,120 --> 00:40:33,080
I found Lucy!

409
00:40:34,060 --> 00:40:35,890
They're camped a half-mile over.

410
00:40:36,060 --> 00:40:38,790
I was swinging back and I saw their smoke.

411
00:40:38,970 --> 00:40:41,280
Bellied up a ridge, and there they were,

412
00:40:41,280 --> 00:40:42,660
right below me.

413
00:40:42,840 --> 00:40:48,130
-Did you see Debbie? -No, but I saw Lucy all right.

414
00:40:48,310 --> 00:40:50,120
She was wearing that blue dress...

415
00:40:50,120 --> 00:40:51,510
What you saw wasn't Lucy.

416
00:40:51,680 --> 00:40:55,240
-Oh, but it was... -What you saw was a buck...

417
00:40:55,420 --> 00:40:57,940
...wearin' Lucy's dress.

418
00:40:58,290 --> 00:41:01,580
I found Lucy back in the canyon.

419
00:41:02,460 --> 00:41:06,050
I wrapped her in my coat.

420
00:41:06,660 --> 00:41:08,820
Buried her with my own hands.

421
00:41:09,800 --> 00:41:13,130
I thought it best to keep it from you.

422
00:41:15,370 --> 00:41:17,100
Did they...

423
00:41:17,440 --> 00:41:19,530
-Was she...? -What do you want me to do?

424
00:41:19,710 --> 00:41:22,870
Draw you a picture? Spell it out?

425
00:41:23,280 --> 00:41:25,010
Don't ever ask me!

426
00:41:25,180 --> 00:41:28,440
As long as you live, don't ever ask me more!

427
00:41:50,970 --> 00:41:54,240
Brad. I'm awful sorry, Brad.

428
00:41:54,410 --> 00:41:58,640
Brad. Wait a minute!

429
00:41:59,550 --> 00:42:02,040
Get back here, Brad!

430
00:42:02,420 --> 00:42:04,910
Brad! Get back here!

431
00:42:55,100 --> 00:42:56,900
Why don't you say it?

432
00:42:57,970 --> 00:43:00,270
We're beaten, and you know it.

433
00:43:01,040 --> 00:43:02,910
No.

434
00:43:03,280 --> 00:43:06,370
Our turnin' back don't mean nothin'.

435
00:43:06,550 --> 00:43:08,810
Not in the long run.

436
00:43:09,080 --> 00:43:11,610
If she's alive, she's safe.

437
00:43:11,790 --> 00:43:14,150
For a while, they'll keep her and they'll

438
00:43:14,320 --> 00:43:17,450
raise her as one of their own until

439
00:43:18,120 --> 00:43:20,790
she's of an age to...

440
00:43:21,260 --> 00:43:23,320
Do you think maybe there's a chance

441
00:43:23,320 --> 00:43:25,720
we still might find her?

442
00:43:25,900 --> 00:43:28,520
An Indian will chase a thing till

443
00:43:28,520 --> 00:43:30,930
he thinks he's chased it enough.

444
00:43:31,200 --> 00:43:32,900
Then he quits.

445
00:43:33,070 --> 00:43:35,340
Same way when he runs.

446
00:43:35,510 --> 00:43:39,100
Seems like he never learns there's such a thing as...

447
00:43:39,280 --> 00:43:42,440
...a critter who'll just keep coming on.

448
00:43:42,850 --> 00:43:45,940
So we'll find 'em in the end. I promise you.

449
00:43:46,120 --> 00:43:48,280
We'll find 'em...

450
00:43:48,460 --> 00:43:52,740
...just as sure as the turnin' of the earth!

451
00:44:42,780 --> 00:44:46,130
-Hi, Ethan. -Hello, sir.

452
00:44:46,310 --> 00:44:48,910
-Hi, Marty. -How are you, sir?

453
00:44:52,420 --> 00:44:54,220
Marty!

454
00:44:59,330 --> 00:45:02,420
You got my letter about your son, Brad?

455
00:45:02,600 --> 00:45:07,090
Yeah. Just about this time a year ago.

456
00:45:10,170 --> 00:45:14,090
Oh, Ethan, this country...

457
00:45:19,750 --> 00:45:21,580
Marty?

458
00:45:24,020 --> 00:45:26,380
Martin Pawley!

459
00:45:30,960 --> 00:45:33,260
Him? Probably forgotten all about you,

460
00:45:33,430 --> 00:45:35,950
Probably can't even call your name to mind!

461
00:45:36,130 --> 00:45:38,360
Her name is Laurie.

462
00:45:40,230 --> 00:45:43,460
But I fairly forgot just how pretty she was.

463
00:45:56,280 --> 00:45:57,980
Ethan.

464
00:45:58,480 --> 00:46:00,870
What about Debbie?

465
00:46:12,130 --> 00:46:15,060
Hey, what are you doin' anyway?

466
00:46:16,440 --> 00:46:18,270
Don't go taking that stuff!

467
00:46:19,170 --> 00:46:21,230
Well, it ain't worth the mending.

468
00:46:21,410 --> 00:46:23,310
What are you gettin' so red in the face about?

469
00:46:23,310 --> 00:46:24,170
I got brothers, ain't I?

470
00:46:24,380 --> 00:46:26,610
Yeah, well, I ain't one of them.

471
00:46:26,780 --> 00:46:29,270
Look here, Martin Pawley, I'm a woman.

472
00:46:29,420 --> 00:46:32,480
We women wash and mend your dirty clothes all your lives.

473
00:46:32,650 --> 00:46:34,350
When you're little, we even wash you!

474
00:46:34,520 --> 00:46:35,670
How you can ever make out to be bashful

475
00:46:35,670 --> 00:46:37,980
in front of a woman, I'll never know.

476
00:46:38,160 --> 00:46:38,940
You talk like a fella

477
00:46:38,940 --> 00:46:40,990
just might as well run around naked.

478
00:46:41,160 --> 00:46:43,150
It wouldn't bother me none.

479
00:46:45,330 --> 00:46:46,410
Sure wouldn't try it

480
00:46:46,410 --> 00:46:48,790
in front of Pa, though, if I was you!

481
00:47:04,120 --> 00:47:06,680
We kept trackin'em till the blizzards hit.

482
00:47:06,850 --> 00:47:09,340
Then we lost their trail.

483
00:47:09,820 --> 00:47:11,980
Don't need to tell you where we went

484
00:47:12,160 --> 00:47:14,650
Fort Richardson, Wingate, Cobb...

485
00:47:14,790 --> 00:47:17,160
Anadarko Agency

486
00:47:17,330 --> 00:47:18,680
Trouble is, we don't know

487
00:47:18,680 --> 00:47:20,320
which band the war party belonged to.

488
00:47:20,500 --> 00:47:22,700
Well, you did all a body could, Ethan.

489
00:47:22,870 --> 00:47:24,850
I got your boy killed.

490
00:47:24,850 --> 00:47:26,400
Don't go blamin' yourself for that.

491
00:47:26,570 --> 00:47:28,630
It's this country that killed my boy.

492
00:47:28,810 --> 00:47:32,040
-Yes, by golly, I tell you Ethan... -Now, Lars,

493
00:47:32,210 --> 00:47:35,170
it just so happens we'd be Texicans.

494
00:47:35,350 --> 00:47:38,760
A Texican is nothing but a human man way out on a limb.

495
00:47:38,760 --> 00:47:41,040
This year and next...

496
00:47:41,220 --> 00:47:42,970
Maybe for a hundred more.

497
00:47:42,980 --> 00:47:45,510
But I don't think it will be forever.

498
00:47:45,690 --> 00:47:49,550
Some day this country's gonna be a fine good place to be.

499
00:47:49,730 --> 00:47:50,950
Maybe it needs our bones

500
00:47:50,950 --> 00:47:53,690
in the ground before that time can come.

501
00:47:53,870 --> 00:47:55,700
Bedtime.

502
00:47:55,900 --> 00:47:58,600
She was a schoolteacher.

503
00:47:59,110 --> 00:48:01,290
Ma, Marty's drawers is a sight.

504
00:48:01,290 --> 00:48:02,450
Would it be all right if we give him

505
00:48:02,450 --> 00:48:03,030
some of Brad's things?

506
00:48:03,210 --> 00:48:05,010
Of course. They're in Grandma's chest.

507
00:48:05,180 --> 00:48:06,910
Ethan, you're going to sleep in the bunkhouse.

508
00:48:06,910 --> 00:48:08,070
My God! The letter!

509
00:48:08,250 --> 00:48:09,410
In the chest!

510
00:48:09,580 --> 00:48:12,560
It came for you, Ethan, last winter.

511
00:48:12,560 --> 00:48:14,040
Charlie McCorry brought it.

512
00:48:15,690 --> 00:48:18,950
I'm looking for that letter, Charlie MacCorry...

513
00:48:19,130 --> 00:48:21,750
That you are in

514
00:48:27,570 --> 00:48:31,490
Here it is. By golly, I forgot.

515
00:48:35,210 --> 00:48:37,270
Excuse me.

516
00:48:48,760 --> 00:48:53,420
Mrs. Jorgensen. Take a look at this.

517
00:48:53,590 --> 00:48:55,170
Just a snip of calico.

518
00:48:55,170 --> 00:48:55,960
Ever see it before?

519
00:48:56,130 --> 00:48:59,430
Maybe on a dress Debbie wore?

520
00:49:00,230 --> 00:49:03,230
Yes, it was an apron.

521
00:49:03,400 --> 00:49:06,630
Ethan. Have they found her yet?

522
00:49:07,840 --> 00:49:09,760
Not yet.

523
00:49:13,080 --> 00:49:15,040
Not yet.

524
00:49:17,750 --> 00:49:19,810
You might at least have left me my britches!

525
00:49:19,990 --> 00:49:21,320
It's time for bed anyway.

526
00:49:21,490 --> 00:49:23,520
Here, try these on.

527
00:49:23,520 --> 00:49:24,650
I ain't gonna.

528
00:49:25,120 --> 00:49:27,460
Well, likely they'll need some takin' in.

529
00:49:27,630 --> 00:49:29,310
Marty, you're that gaunt.

530
00:49:29,310 --> 00:49:31,320
Ma's having turkey for dinner tomorrow.

531
00:49:31,500 --> 00:49:35,350
Laurie, come. Let the boys get to bed.

532
00:49:35,570 --> 00:49:37,590
All right, Pa.

533
00:49:42,480 --> 00:49:45,210
-Good night, Marty. -Good night, Laurie.

534
00:49:45,380 --> 00:49:49,110
-'Night, Mr. Edwards. -'Night, Ms. Jorgensen.

535
00:49:54,950 --> 00:49:58,120
Jorgensen's been runnin' my cattle with his own.

536
00:49:59,030 --> 00:50:00,980
Your cattle?

537
00:50:01,160 --> 00:50:02,720
You mean Debbie's cattle.

538
00:50:02,900 --> 00:50:06,000
He's agreed to take you on and split the increase

539
00:50:06,000 --> 00:50:08,530
in my herd while I'm gone.

540
00:50:08,700 --> 00:50:10,360
I'm pushin' on tomorrow.

541
00:50:10,740 --> 00:50:12,530
Well, I sure ain't gonna stay here!

542
00:50:12,530 --> 00:50:14,330
I started out lookin' for Debbie,

543
00:50:14,510 --> 00:50:16,300
-I intend to keep on. -Why?

544
00:50:16,480 --> 00:50:17,810
Why?

545
00:50:17,980 --> 00:50:21,330
-Well, because she is my... -She's your nothing!

546
00:50:21,510 --> 00:50:23,350
She's no kin to you at all!

547
00:50:24,120 --> 00:50:27,010
I always kind of thought she was.

548
00:50:27,190 --> 00:50:29,350
The way her folks took me in and raised me...

549
00:50:29,520 --> 00:50:32,250
-That don't make you no kin. -All right, maybe it don't.

550
00:50:32,430 --> 00:50:35,520
-But I intend to keep on lookin' anyway. -How?

551
00:50:35,700 --> 00:50:37,930
You got any horses, or money to buy 'em?

552
00:50:38,130 --> 00:50:40,260
You ain't even got money for cartridges.

553
00:50:40,830 --> 00:50:44,260
Jorgensen's offerin' you a good livin' here.

554
00:50:48,040 --> 00:50:50,200
Martin, I want you to know...

555
00:50:50,370 --> 00:50:52,240
I know what you want me to know!

556
00:50:52,410 --> 00:50:55,210
I've got no kin, no money, no horses!

557
00:50:55,380 --> 00:50:59,070
All I got here is a bunch of dead-man's clothes to wear!

558
00:50:59,250 --> 00:51:02,580
You told me that already, so, shut your mouth!

559
00:51:14,600 --> 00:51:18,830
-Mornin', Laurie. -Mornin', Marty. Did you sleep well?

560
00:51:19,000 --> 00:51:21,800
Well, no.

561
00:51:21,970 --> 00:51:26,260
I kind of tossed and turned...

562
00:51:26,440 --> 00:51:28,330
...and dreamed.

563
00:51:40,920 --> 00:51:43,220
I'll get your coffee.

564
00:51:45,030 --> 00:51:46,860
You know, Laurie, I...

565
00:51:47,030 --> 00:51:48,620
...I was thinking

566
00:51:48,800 --> 00:51:52,360
maybe it's time you and me started goin' steady, huh?

567
00:51:53,300 --> 00:51:55,420
You and me have been goin' steady

568
00:51:55,430 --> 00:51:57,120
since we was three years old.

569
00:51:57,310 --> 00:52:00,930
-We have? -About time you found out about it!

570
00:52:01,110 --> 00:52:04,170
Gosh, Laurie, I've always been fond of you, but...

571
00:52:04,350 --> 00:52:08,170
...with all this trouble with Debbie and Ethan, I...

572
00:52:08,350 --> 00:52:10,880
Ethan rode on an hour ago.

573
00:52:11,350 --> 00:52:13,460
I don't know what you can do about

574
00:52:13,460 --> 00:52:14,810
findin' Debbie that he can't.

575
00:52:14,990 --> 00:52:17,150
He'll find her now, Martin. Honest he will!

576
00:52:17,890 --> 00:52:20,160
That's what I'm afraid of, Laurie,

577
00:52:20,330 --> 00:52:22,460
him finding her!

578
00:52:22,830 --> 00:52:26,490
I've seen his eyes at the very word "Comanche."

579
00:52:26,670 --> 00:52:29,400
I've seen him take his knife and...

580
00:52:30,570 --> 00:52:32,730
Never mind. He's a man that can go crazy wild!

581
00:52:32,910 --> 00:52:35,870
And I intend to be there to stop him, in case he does.

582
00:52:36,210 --> 00:52:38,310
I was hopin' I could hold you here,

583
00:52:38,310 --> 00:52:40,030
but I guess I knew better.

584
00:52:41,520 --> 00:52:42,880
Here.

585
00:52:43,050 --> 00:52:44,920
I stole that for you.

586
00:52:54,100 --> 00:52:56,590
"I...bought..."

587
00:52:56,730 --> 00:52:59,430
Here, let me read it for you.

588
00:53:00,370 --> 00:53:02,860
"I bought a small-sized dress off of an Indian.

589
00:53:03,000 --> 00:53:05,550
"If this here's a piece of your child's dress,

590
00:53:05,550 --> 00:53:06,530
bring the reward.

591
00:53:06,710 --> 00:53:08,200
"I know where they've gone. "

592
00:53:08,380 --> 00:53:11,610
-"Jerem Futterman." -Jerem Futterman!

593
00:53:11,810 --> 00:53:14,060
He's got a small trading post

594
00:53:14,060 --> 00:53:15,440
on the south fork of the Brazos.

595
00:53:15,620 --> 00:53:16,750
Listen, I just gotta get me a horse!

596
00:53:16,750 --> 00:53:18,040
Do you think your Pa...

597
00:53:18,220 --> 00:53:19,510
Finish your breakfast!

598
00:53:19,510 --> 00:53:21,350
I've got to find him!

599
00:53:21,520 --> 00:53:24,190
All right, go on and find him!

600
00:53:24,190 --> 00:53:26,850
Oh, Laurie, don't you understand?

601
00:53:36,610 --> 00:53:39,100
But that's your own good horse!

602
00:53:39,310 --> 00:53:41,040
You take him and welcome!

603
00:53:41,210 --> 00:53:44,370
But don't you count on findin' me here when you get back.

604
00:53:44,550 --> 00:53:47,070
I've been hanging around this Godforsaken place...

605
00:53:47,250 --> 00:53:49,240
...for two long years waiting for you.

606
00:53:49,250 --> 00:53:51,810
I ain't cut out to be no old maid!

607
00:53:52,620 --> 00:53:56,550
I'm sorry, Laurie, but I just gotta catch up with Ethan.

608
00:53:56,730 --> 00:53:59,520
Well, go ahead and catch up with him!

609
00:54:16,650 --> 00:54:18,480
-Futterman? -Yeah.

610
00:54:18,650 --> 00:54:20,540
Let's talk.

611
00:54:25,490 --> 00:54:29,150
-You sent me a letter. -Yeah?

612
00:54:29,360 --> 00:54:31,420
About a dress.

613
00:54:44,470 --> 00:54:45,800
How'd you come by it?

614
00:54:45,970 --> 00:54:48,930
-You said there was a $1,000 reward. -That's what I said.

615
00:54:49,110 --> 00:54:50,940
Got it with you?

616
00:54:51,150 --> 00:54:53,250
You'll get the reward when I find her,

617
00:54:53,260 --> 00:54:54,310
and if she's still alive.

618
00:54:54,480 --> 00:54:56,910
A man's got a right to expect some kind of payment.

619
00:54:57,090 --> 00:54:59,940
I laid out for that dress and sendin' you that writing.

620
00:55:02,420 --> 00:55:06,280
-Twenty Yankee dollars. -A man's time is worth something.

621
00:55:06,590 --> 00:55:08,080
Talk.

622
00:55:10,800 --> 00:55:12,860
A young buck fetched it in late last summer.

623
00:55:13,030 --> 00:55:15,530
Said it belonged to a captive child of Chief Scar.

624
00:55:15,670 --> 00:55:18,970
Scar? We ain't never heard of him, have we?

625
00:55:19,140 --> 00:55:20,820
Me neither. But this buck claimed

626
00:55:20,820 --> 00:55:22,200
he was a big war chief...

627
00:55:22,410 --> 00:55:24,610
-...with the Nawyecky Comanches. -Keep talkin'.

628
00:55:24,780 --> 00:55:27,190
Scar's band was headed north to winter at Fort Wingate,

629
00:55:27,190 --> 00:55:28,550
eatin' agency beef.

630
00:55:28,720 --> 00:55:31,140
That's what this buck said. Maybe he lied.

631
00:55:32,120 --> 00:55:33,710
Maybe you lie.

632
00:55:33,920 --> 00:55:36,290
In that case, my friend, you won't find her...

633
00:55:36,460 --> 00:55:38,690
...and I won't get my $1,000 dollars.

634
00:55:38,860 --> 00:55:41,390
Look, You can spend the night.

635
00:55:41,560 --> 00:55:44,230
Cards, a jug, if you like...

636
00:55:44,230 --> 00:55:45,350
No thanks.

637
00:55:46,630 --> 00:55:48,520
Don't forget to come back with my $1,000!

638
00:55:48,700 --> 00:55:50,930
It ain't yours yet!

639
00:55:52,370 --> 00:55:54,500
Hey, Ethan.

640
00:55:55,710 --> 00:55:59,200
Do you have a feeling that maybe we're being followed?

641
00:55:59,380 --> 00:56:01,750
That's the Indian in you. Go to sleep.

642
00:56:01,950 --> 00:56:04,580
Them horses there... they're sure actin' mighty nervous.

643
00:56:04,750 --> 00:56:08,020
They smell a change in the weather.

644
00:56:15,460 --> 00:56:18,350
Don't put any more wood on the fire.

645
00:56:18,530 --> 00:56:21,160
-I'm burning up. -We might get a frost before mornin'.

646
00:56:21,340 --> 00:56:24,530
I'm getting to be like old Mose Harper.

647
00:56:24,740 --> 00:56:27,660
My bones are cold tonight.

648
00:56:29,260 --> 00:56:29,960
You know...

649
00:56:31,950 --> 00:56:33,200
...it's funny, but

650
00:56:33,200 --> 00:56:36,430
last winter when we passed through Fort Wingate...

651
00:56:36,600 --> 00:56:38,550
...I didn't have any recollection of

652
00:56:38,550 --> 00:56:40,830
a mention of Nawyecky Comanches.

653
00:56:41,000 --> 00:56:43,220
Not so funny when you recollect

654
00:56:43,220 --> 00:56:44,390
what "Nawyecky" means.

655
00:56:44,570 --> 00:56:47,500
-What's that? -Sort of like "roundabout."

656
00:56:47,680 --> 00:56:50,210
A man says he's goin' one place,

657
00:56:50,210 --> 00:56:52,240
means to go to the other.

658
00:57:03,530 --> 00:57:06,410
Come on, Ethan. Don't put any more wood on the fire!

659
00:57:06,600 --> 00:57:08,460
I'm burning up.

660
00:57:16,200 --> 00:57:18,930
-Comfortable? -Ethan, are you all right?

661
00:57:19,340 --> 00:57:21,640
I'm just saying good night to you.

662
00:57:21,840 --> 00:57:24,400
Well, good night!

663
00:57:46,470 --> 00:57:50,390
-Good night! -Good night!

664
00:58:20,140 --> 00:58:22,090
Futterman!

665
00:58:36,650 --> 00:58:39,710
Thanks, you did fine.

666
00:58:42,020 --> 00:58:44,510
Why, that's Mr. Futterman!

667
00:58:44,660 --> 00:58:46,620
Ethan, what are you doin' anyway?

668
00:58:46,800 --> 00:58:48,870
I'm getting my money back,

669
00:58:48,870 --> 00:58:50,720
you idiot! What do you suppose!

670
00:58:51,170 --> 00:58:52,530
We did all right.

671
00:58:56,870 --> 00:58:59,740
We? Why you just staked me out there,

672
00:58:59,740 --> 00:59:00,970
like a piece of bait!

673
00:59:01,140 --> 00:59:03,750
You built up the fire. You fixed it

674
00:59:03,750 --> 00:59:05,840
so I could get my brains blown out!

675
00:59:06,010 --> 00:59:08,380
What if you had missed?

676
00:59:08,580 --> 00:59:11,010
It never occurred to me.

677
00:59:13,820 --> 00:59:16,480
Let's get out of here.

678
00:59:25,080 --> 00:59:27,850
Howdy, Mr. Jorgensen.

679
00:59:28,050 --> 00:59:31,440
-Charlie! -Got me a letter here.

680
00:59:31,620 --> 00:59:34,620
By golly, a letter?

681
00:59:34,790 --> 00:59:36,420
It's for Ms. Laurie.

682
00:59:36,600 --> 00:59:40,120
Two letters in one year! By golly!

683
00:59:40,300 --> 00:59:43,360
Mama! Mama! It's Charlie McCorry.

684
00:59:43,570 --> 00:59:45,680
He's come with a letter.

685
00:59:45,680 --> 00:59:47,490
He's come a courtin' too, by golly!

686
00:59:47,670 --> 00:59:49,770
Come on

687
00:59:50,980 --> 00:59:53,710
Good morning, Charlie.

688
00:59:53,880 --> 00:59:56,710
Laurie, here's a letter for you. Charlie brought it.

689
00:59:56,880 --> 00:59:57,870
I figured it might be the news

690
00:59:57,870 --> 01:00:00,670
you've been waiting for, so l...

691
01:00:00,850 --> 01:00:02,840
-Thank you, Charlie. -You're welcome.

692
01:00:03,020 --> 01:00:04,830
Say, I brought you some boiled sweets.

693
01:00:04,830 --> 01:00:06,180
Thank you, Charlie!

694
01:00:06,360 --> 01:00:09,890
Let's sit down while Laurie reads the letter.

695
01:00:10,100 --> 01:00:11,890
I reckon, I really ought to be going...

696
01:00:12,100 --> 01:00:15,620
No. You'll stay, Charlie.

697
01:00:15,800 --> 01:00:18,040
After all, Charlie brought the letter.

698
01:00:18,040 --> 01:00:19,160
He's got a right to listen too.

699
01:00:19,340 --> 01:00:23,300
Come on, read the letter.

700
01:00:24,380 --> 01:00:25,690
But, Ma, it's my letter!

701
01:00:25,690 --> 01:00:27,470
Why, sure, but read it.

702
01:00:27,650 --> 01:00:30,340
Go ahead. Read it.

703
01:00:38,220 --> 01:00:39,750
Please.

704
01:00:41,160 --> 01:00:43,080
"Dear Ms. Laury..."

705
01:00:43,260 --> 01:00:45,250
He spelled it with a "y" instead of an "ie."

706
01:00:45,430 --> 01:00:47,920
-You'd think he'd know better. -Oh, spelling...please!

707
01:00:48,130 --> 01:00:50,860
What's the difference? Read the letter!

708
01:00:52,240 --> 01:00:57,160
"Dear Ms. Laury: I take pencil in hand to let you know...

709
01:00:57,340 --> 01:00:59,300
"...Ethan and me are still trying

710
01:00:59,310 --> 01:01:01,270
to catch up with them Comanches...

711
01:01:01,450 --> 01:01:04,900
"...the late Mr. Futterman told us about."

712
01:01:05,420 --> 01:01:06,850
The "late" Mr. Futterman?

713
01:01:07,020 --> 01:01:09,750
That means Mr. Futterman is dead, by golly.

714
01:01:09,920 --> 01:01:13,550
Oh, the poor man! Go ahead, Laurie.

715
01:01:14,290 --> 01:01:18,550
"We cut north through Indian territory..."

716
01:01:18,560 --> 01:01:20,690
"...and did not have no trouble..."

717
01:01:20,870 --> 01:01:23,930
"...finding Kiowas and Wichitas..."

718
01:01:24,100 --> 01:01:26,530
"...and even some Comanches..."

719
01:01:26,710 --> 01:01:29,230
"...camped by one of the agencies."

720
01:01:29,870 --> 01:01:32,370
"But none of them was Nawyeckies..."

721
01:01:32,540 --> 01:01:37,210
"...nor claimed to know a war chief called Scar."

722
01:01:37,450 --> 01:01:39,080
Scar?

723
01:01:41,250 --> 01:01:47,320
"He's the one the late Mr. Futterman said had Debbie."

724
01:01:48,190 --> 01:01:51,490
"At one of the agencies..."

725
01:01:51,700 --> 01:01:54,820
"...we outfitted with all kinds of trade goods...

726
01:01:55,000 --> 01:01:56,960
"...figuring that'd make it easier

727
01:01:56,970 --> 01:02:00,890
for us to come and go...

728
01:02:03,110 --> 01:02:04,960
"You'd laugh if I told you..."

729
01:02:04,960 --> 01:02:09,210
"...what was our biggest seller. "

730
01:02:58,460 --> 01:03:00,950
Let's go. I think I stumbled onto something.

731
01:03:01,130 --> 01:03:02,460
Scar...you found him?

732
01:03:02,630 --> 01:03:05,130
When are you gonna learn to keep your big mouth shut?

733
01:03:05,300 --> 01:03:07,130
Get your horse, and let's get out of here!

734
01:03:07,310 --> 01:03:10,540
-I just bought me a good blanket. -Forget it. Move!

735
01:03:15,480 --> 01:03:19,210
I heard that a band of hostile Comanches...

736
01:03:19,380 --> 01:03:21,550
...came through less than a week ago.

737
01:03:21,720 --> 01:03:24,710
I asked if a white girl was with them.

738
01:03:24,890 --> 01:03:26,880
They got sullen and suspicious.

739
01:03:27,060 --> 01:03:30,720
-You think it might have been... -I don't know!

740
01:03:35,800 --> 01:03:38,560
What's she following us for?

741
01:03:39,370 --> 01:03:43,500
Hey, you! You go on back now!

742
01:03:43,940 --> 01:03:47,000
Look, I changed my mind. You can keep your blanket.

743
01:03:51,380 --> 01:03:54,610
Look, you don't understand. I don't want it!

744
01:03:54,820 --> 01:03:57,740
You don't understand, you chunkhead!

745
01:03:57,920 --> 01:04:00,050
You didn't buy any blanket,

746
01:04:00,230 --> 01:04:01,590
you bought her!

747
01:04:01,760 --> 01:04:03,850
You got yourself a wife, sonny!

748
01:04:04,030 --> 01:04:07,590
Oh, no! Ethan, tell her to go back!

749
01:04:07,770 --> 01:04:10,960
What? And have her whole family after our scalps...

750
01:04:11,140 --> 01:04:14,900
...for flauntin' one of their womenfolk? No, sir!

751
01:04:15,070 --> 01:04:17,300
Come on, Mrs. Pawley.

752
01:04:17,480 --> 01:04:21,140
Come on, Mrs. Pawley. Join our merry group.

753
01:04:21,350 --> 01:04:23,910
Mrs. Pawley?

754
01:04:24,080 --> 01:04:26,920
Oh,no

755
01:04:27,120 --> 01:04:31,150
"There is one other thing I got to tell you..."

756
01:04:31,360 --> 01:04:34,620
"...before you hear it from Ethan."

757
01:04:35,930 --> 01:04:38,990
"How I got myself..."

758
01:04:39,360 --> 01:04:40,660
"...a wife..."

759
01:04:41,900 --> 01:04:44,790
-He did? -Good!

760
01:04:44,970 --> 01:04:47,300
A young man should get married early in life.

761
01:04:47,310 --> 01:04:48,790
Right, Mama?

762
01:04:52,810 --> 01:04:56,370
Go ahead and read the letter, Laurie.

763
01:04:58,450 --> 01:05:03,440
"A little Comanche squaw..."

764
01:05:03,960 --> 01:05:06,120
Squaw!

765
01:05:07,530 --> 01:05:10,950
Laurie, you come back and read the letter, please!

766
01:05:11,130 --> 01:05:13,790
This is a shame.

767
01:05:13,970 --> 01:05:16,300
Come back and read it, please!

768
01:05:17,440 --> 01:05:21,170
Mama, here, you read the letter.

769
01:05:21,940 --> 01:05:26,670
Charlie. My wife was a schoolteacher. She reads good.

770
01:05:28,150 --> 01:05:29,480
I'll read it.

771
01:05:29,650 --> 01:05:33,440
So he married a Comanche squaw.

772
01:05:36,120 --> 01:05:38,450
My god

773
01:05:41,330 --> 01:05:47,620
"She wasn't near...as old as you..."

774
01:05:47,970 --> 01:05:51,300
How old does he think I am?

775
01:05:52,240 --> 01:05:56,830
Hey, look! Coffee. Me. Coffee.

776
01:06:02,080 --> 01:06:06,470
Could I have a little, Mrs. Pawley?

777
01:06:07,590 --> 01:06:09,540
Yes sir

778
01:06:09,720 --> 01:06:11,230
Looks like Mrs. Pawley's gonna make you

779
01:06:11,230 --> 01:06:13,490
a fine, dutiful wife.

780
01:06:13,660 --> 01:06:16,490
Oh, cut it out, will you?

781
01:06:19,060 --> 01:06:24,730
Oh, look. I sure wish I could make you understand.

782
01:06:26,370 --> 01:06:28,070
Look?

783
01:06:32,240 --> 01:06:33,570
Look?

784
01:06:33,750 --> 01:06:38,940
She says her name is Wild Goose Flying in The Night Sky.

785
01:06:39,120 --> 01:06:43,350
But she'll answer to "Look," if that pleases you.

786
01:07:15,750 --> 01:07:19,780
You know, that's grounds for divorce in Texas!

787
01:07:21,530 --> 01:07:23,150
You're really rough!

788
01:07:23,330 --> 01:07:26,890
Well, I don't think it's a dead-bird funny!

789
01:07:27,070 --> 01:07:29,430
Look, if you really wanna do some good,

790
01:07:29,440 --> 01:07:31,300
why don't you ask her where Scar is?

791
01:07:36,610 --> 01:07:38,560
She heard you.

792
01:07:46,120 --> 01:07:49,310
-You ask her! -Look. Scar?

793
01:07:49,490 --> 01:07:51,180
Do you know where he went?

794
01:07:51,360 --> 01:07:53,290
Do you know where he went? Did he have a girl with him?

795
01:07:53,290 --> 01:07:54,350
A white girl?

796
01:07:59,830 --> 01:08:02,860
No, not a woman. It's...

797
01:08:04,470 --> 01:08:06,300
Sister!

798
01:08:20,990 --> 01:08:22,980
Martin!

799
01:08:32,160 --> 01:08:34,190
Look's gone!

800
01:08:34,830 --> 01:08:36,820
Pulled out in the night.

801
01:08:38,040 --> 01:08:42,560
She ain't goin' back to her family. That's for certain.

802
01:08:42,740 --> 01:08:45,660
She took off the way that arrow is pointing.

803
01:08:45,840 --> 01:08:48,470
Think maybe we ought to follow her?

804
01:08:48,650 --> 01:08:50,510
How should I know?

805
01:08:50,680 --> 01:08:52,980
She's your wife.

806
01:08:55,820 --> 01:08:58,190
"Maybe she left other signs for us to follow but...

807
01:08:58,360 --> 01:08:59,910
"...we'll never know..."

808
01:09:00,120 --> 01:09:04,410
"...because it snowed that day and all the next week."

809
01:09:07,670 --> 01:09:10,000
We were headin' north through buff alo country...

810
01:09:10,170 --> 01:09:12,180
...when somethin' happened that

811
01:09:12,180 --> 01:09:13,900
I ain't got straight in my own mind yet.

812
01:09:14,070 --> 01:09:16,730
On this day we sighted a small herd.

813
01:09:16,910 --> 01:09:18,240
We needed meat,

814
01:09:18,410 --> 01:09:20,370
so we circled around...

815
01:09:20,370 --> 01:09:21,900
...and came up on them on foot.

816
01:09:58,580 --> 01:10:01,110
-Ethan, that don't make no sense! -Hunger! Empty bellies!

817
01:10:01,290 --> 01:10:03,880
That's the sense!

818
01:10:04,060 --> 01:10:06,110
Ethan, stop it!

819
01:10:14,570 --> 01:10:17,060
At least they won't feed any Comanches this winter!

820
01:10:18,700 --> 01:10:21,930
Listen! Listen!

821
01:10:22,110 --> 01:10:23,970
Listen! Listen!

822
01:10:36,650 --> 01:10:38,420
Come on

823
01:11:29,410 --> 01:11:31,470
It was the Nawyecky Comanches, all right.

824
01:11:31,680 --> 01:11:34,770
The ones we'd been looking for all this time.

825
01:11:46,520 --> 01:11:48,290
Marty!

826
01:12:07,180 --> 01:12:09,070
It's Look.

827
01:12:10,580 --> 01:12:12,210
Look?

828
01:12:13,750 --> 01:12:15,910
What did them soldiers have to go and kill her for?

829
01:12:15,910 --> 01:12:17,350
She never done nobody any harm.

830
01:12:17,520 --> 01:12:18,890
We've got to catch up with them,

831
01:12:18,890 --> 01:12:20,120
maybe they've got Debbie with them!

832
01:12:20,320 --> 01:12:24,090
Maybe they've got that chief they call Scar.

833
01:12:24,260 --> 01:12:26,920
So, we figured Debbie'd been in the village.

834
01:12:27,100 --> 01:12:28,640
What Look was doin' there...

835
01:12:28,640 --> 01:12:29,930
whether she'd come to warn 'em...

836
01:12:30,100 --> 01:12:32,740
...or maybe to find Debbie for me...

837
01:12:32,740 --> 01:12:34,420
there's no way of knowing.

838
01:13:18,280 --> 01:13:22,740
Come on, move on...

839
01:13:23,150 --> 01:13:25,780
Come on, move along! Come on!

840
01:13:36,830 --> 01:13:41,760
Come on, hurry up.

841
01:13:42,310 --> 01:13:44,870
-Good evening. -Yes?

842
01:13:45,040 --> 01:13:47,430
We're looking for a girl. A white girl. A captive.

843
01:13:47,610 --> 01:13:49,600
Should be about 14 now.

844
01:13:49,780 --> 01:13:51,610
Fourteen? We have two about that age.

845
01:13:51,780 --> 01:13:53,110
-Where? -Sergeant

846
01:13:53,280 --> 01:13:55,050
All the white women are in the chapel.

847
01:13:55,220 --> 01:13:56,550
What's this girl to you?

848
01:13:56,720 --> 01:13:58,680
-She's my... -She's my niece.

849
01:13:59,990 --> 01:14:01,860
One moment.

850
01:14:04,360 --> 01:14:06,490
-White women? -Yes, sir.

851
01:14:32,560 --> 01:14:34,680
Will you stand up?

852
01:14:35,160 --> 01:14:36,520
Stand up, please.

853
01:14:42,230 --> 01:14:43,890
Debbie?

854
01:14:59,750 --> 01:15:02,120
It's hard to believe they're white.

855
01:15:02,620 --> 01:15:04,710
They ain't white!

856
01:15:04,890 --> 01:15:06,250
Not any more.

857
01:15:06,420 --> 01:15:08,260
They are Comanches!

858
01:15:08,430 --> 01:15:11,220
Where are your casualties?

859
01:15:29,880 --> 01:15:31,800
Maybe you can help us identify them.

860
01:15:31,800 --> 01:15:33,410
All white. All captives.

861
01:15:33,580 --> 01:15:35,950
There's the white girl there.

862
01:15:46,060 --> 01:15:47,620
No.

863
01:15:50,900 --> 01:15:53,790
"So we're setting out for

864
01:15:53,790 --> 01:15:57,030
New Mexico territory in the morning.

865
01:15:57,270 --> 01:16:00,570
"I am sorry I won't be back

866
01:16:00,740 --> 01:16:03,940
for Christmas again this year.

867
01:16:06,620 --> 01:16:08,620
"I set pencil aside and hope

868
01:16:08,620 --> 01:16:10,180
you are enjoying good health.

869
01:16:10,350 --> 01:16:12,910
"And your folks the same."

870
01:16:13,090 --> 01:16:16,080
"I remain, respectfully..."

871
01:16:16,460 --> 01:16:19,950
"...yours truly, Martin Pawley."

872
01:16:21,570 --> 01:16:24,490
They'll never find that girl.

873
01:16:24,670 --> 01:16:27,260
Never!

874
01:16:35,180 --> 01:16:37,880
"Yours truly."

875
01:16:39,520 --> 01:16:43,040
He had to sign his whole name, "Martin Pawley."

876
01:16:43,220 --> 01:16:46,020
He couldn't write just "Marty"!

877
01:16:47,320 --> 01:16:50,890
-I don't care if he never comes back! -Laurie! Laurie!

878
01:16:51,100 --> 01:16:53,340
Charlie, you stay for supper.

879
01:16:53,350 --> 01:16:54,660
I won't take "no" for an answer.

880
01:16:54,830 --> 01:16:58,050
The thought of saying "no" never entered my head,

881
01:16:58,050 --> 01:16:59,660
Mrs. Jorgensen.

882
01:17:00,040 --> 01:17:03,170
Ain't no place I'd rather be than right here...

883
01:17:03,840 --> 01:17:05,830
...right now.

884
01:17:49,250 --> 01:17:51,880
-Recognize it? -That?

885
01:17:52,060 --> 01:17:55,840
Couldn't be two like that in the whole world! Mose!

886
01:17:56,290 --> 01:17:58,780
Mose Harper!

887
01:18:01,700 --> 01:18:04,090
-Mose -Nice to meet you

888
01:18:04,270 --> 01:18:06,660
Mose, you look shabbier than ever!

889
01:18:06,970 --> 01:18:09,270
-How about a drink? -Yes, sir.

890
01:18:09,440 --> 01:18:11,600
Ain't been too good.

891
01:18:11,780 --> 01:18:13,940
No, sir. Not too good.

892
01:18:14,110 --> 01:18:16,910
-Getting old. -You were born old.

893
01:18:17,080 --> 01:18:20,280
Been helpin' you, Ethan. Been lookin' all the time.

894
01:18:20,450 --> 01:18:23,480
The reward still stands.

895
01:18:24,760 --> 01:18:28,710
Don't want no money, Ethan. No money, Marty.

896
01:18:28,890 --> 01:18:33,450
Just a roof over old Mose's head.

897
01:18:33,630 --> 01:18:36,160
And a rocking chair by the fire.

898
01:18:36,330 --> 01:18:40,000
My own rocking chair by the fire, Marty.

899
01:18:40,200 --> 01:18:42,100
You help us find the girl and

900
01:18:42,100 --> 01:18:43,230
you've got your rocking chair.

901
01:18:43,410 --> 01:18:45,500
Swear it, Ethan? Given word?

902
01:18:45,710 --> 01:18:48,200
I told you, didn't I?

903
01:18:48,480 --> 01:18:51,900
Ethan, I found a man who's seen her.

904
01:18:52,080 --> 01:18:54,350
He knows where little Debbie is!

905
01:18:54,520 --> 01:18:56,940
Where is he? Who is this man?

906
01:18:57,120 --> 01:18:59,820
-Promise? -Who is the man?

907
01:19:00,260 --> 01:19:02,590
I am this man, Seor.

908
01:19:03,130 --> 01:19:06,290
Emilio G. Fernandez Figueroa.

909
01:19:06,460 --> 01:19:09,160
At your service. For a price.

910
01:19:09,330 --> 01:19:11,600
Always for a price.

911
01:19:24,150 --> 01:19:27,680
-Sir, I'd like to... -Wait till you grow up.

912
01:19:54,310 --> 01:19:56,910
Let's talk a little business.

913
01:19:58,480 --> 01:20:00,180
Why not?

914
01:20:12,400 --> 01:20:16,390
Aunt, please give me Fried bean

915
01:20:32,050 --> 01:20:33,380
Let's go.

916
01:20:33,550 --> 01:20:36,380
-But I'm hungry! -While you're fillin' your belly...

917
01:20:36,550 --> 01:20:39,410
...I'm goin' out to meet a Comanche named Cicatriz.

918
01:20:39,590 --> 01:20:41,620
Never heard of him.

919
01:20:41,830 --> 01:20:45,920
"Cicatriz" is Mexican for "scar."

920
01:22:07,280 --> 01:22:09,470
Medicine country, huh?

921
01:22:09,650 --> 01:22:12,140
Bad medicine, I think.

922
01:22:35,240 --> 01:22:40,700
-This is the great Cicatriz, War Chief. -Scar, huh?

923
01:22:44,750 --> 01:22:47,880
Plain to see how you got your name.

924
01:22:48,890 --> 01:22:51,380
You, Big Shoulders.

925
01:22:51,520 --> 01:22:55,720
The young one, He Who Follows.

926
01:22:55,960 --> 01:23:00,560
You speak pretty good American for a Comanche.

927
01:23:00,730 --> 01:23:02,960
Did someone teach you?

928
01:23:11,240 --> 01:23:14,870
That's right. We've come to trade. Only not out here.

929
01:23:15,050 --> 01:23:18,040
I don't stand talkin' in the wind.

930
01:23:43,140 --> 01:23:47,240
You speak good Comanche. Did someone teach you?

931
01:23:48,150 --> 01:23:51,570
-You, stay out here. -Not likely.

932
01:23:57,120 --> 01:23:58,900
His sons are dead.

933
01:23:58,900 --> 01:24:01,940
So his wives sit on the honor side of his lodge.

934
01:24:07,760 --> 01:24:10,060
Are all those his wives?

935
01:24:10,230 --> 01:24:13,120
Two sons killed by white men.

936
01:24:13,800 --> 01:24:18,330
For each son, I take many...

937
01:24:18,540 --> 01:24:20,530
Scalps.

938
01:24:54,280 --> 01:24:56,440
We've seen scalps before.

939
01:24:58,450 --> 01:25:00,810
Seen this before?

940
01:25:07,320 --> 01:25:09,660
I came to trade, not to admire his collection.

941
01:25:09,830 --> 01:25:10,980
Tell him we'll pitch camp

942
01:25:10,980 --> 01:25:12,820
on the other side of the creek and

943
01:25:13,030 --> 01:25:16,490
-...talk tomorrow. -Tomorrow?

944
01:25:30,650 --> 01:25:32,560
It is not that I am afraid.

945
01:25:32,560 --> 01:25:35,310
Don't apologize. You got well paid.

946
01:25:36,390 --> 01:25:39,580
But he knows who you are, and why you're here.

947
01:25:39,580 --> 01:25:41,050
This, I did not know.

948
01:25:42,990 --> 01:25:46,620
Take it. I do not want blood money.

949
01:26:04,450 --> 01:26:07,780
Do you think old Scar means to kill us?

950
01:26:07,950 --> 01:26:09,840
He's got to.

951
01:26:10,020 --> 01:26:13,110
We've been asking for it for five years.

952
01:26:13,290 --> 01:26:17,520
Why didn't he make his move back there?

953
01:26:18,460 --> 01:26:23,060
Hospitality, I guess. Comanche hospitality.

954
01:26:25,400 --> 01:26:28,460
Why? Do you want to pull out too?

955
01:26:32,740 --> 01:26:35,170
Big Shoulders!

956
01:26:46,790 --> 01:26:48,450
Debbie?

957
01:26:50,590 --> 01:26:55,290
Debbie, don't you remember? I'm Martin, your brother.

958
01:26:56,200 --> 01:26:58,000
Remember?

959
01:26:59,140 --> 01:27:01,630
Debbie, remember back...

960
01:27:02,140 --> 01:27:06,240
Do you remember how I used to let you ride my horse?

961
01:27:06,740 --> 01:27:09,230
And tell you stories?

962
01:27:10,450 --> 01:27:12,440
Don't you remember me, Debbie?

963
01:27:12,920 --> 01:27:14,940
I remember.

964
01:27:15,420 --> 01:27:17,510
For always.

965
01:27:18,520 --> 01:27:20,510
First I prayed to you,

966
01:27:20,960 --> 01:27:22,980
to come and get me...

967
01:27:23,160 --> 01:27:24,490
...to take me home.

968
01:27:24,960 --> 01:27:26,920
You didn't come.

969
01:27:28,270 --> 01:27:30,150
I've come now, Debbie.

970
01:27:30,800 --> 01:27:32,860
These are my people.

971
01:27:34,470 --> 01:27:37,740
Go! Go, Martin! Please!

972
01:27:38,740 --> 01:27:40,330
Stand aside, Martin!

973
01:27:44,510 --> 01:27:46,710
No, you don't, Ethan!

974
01:27:46,880 --> 01:27:49,550
Ethan! No, you don't!

975
01:27:50,850 --> 01:27:53,240
Stand aside!

976
01:28:11,710 --> 01:28:14,840
Debbie!

977
01:30:17,530 --> 01:30:19,300
Well

978
01:30:19,540 --> 01:30:21,430
Looks as though I'm gonna have to

979
01:30:21,430 --> 01:30:23,700
open that shoulder again.

980
01:30:23,910 --> 01:30:26,400
To get the poison out.

981
01:30:26,540 --> 01:30:27,420
Sure beats me, Ethan...

982
01:30:27,420 --> 01:30:29,170
how you could've stayed alive this long.

983
01:30:29,350 --> 01:30:30,680
I want you

984
01:30:30,850 --> 01:30:32,910
Read this.

985
01:30:44,790 --> 01:30:46,280
"I..."

986
01:30:47,160 --> 01:30:50,330
"...Ethan Edwards..."

987
01:30:50,500 --> 01:30:55,130
"...being of a sound mind..."

988
01:30:55,440 --> 01:30:56,930
"...and..."

989
01:30:57,070 --> 01:31:01,830
"...without any blood kin..."

990
01:31:06,350 --> 01:31:10,380
"...do hereby..."

991
01:31:11,590 --> 01:31:14,750
Bequeath. It means "leave."

992
01:31:15,460 --> 01:31:17,760
"...bequeath..."

993
01:31:18,330 --> 01:31:22,560
"...all my property..."

994
01:31:22,730 --> 01:31:25,220
"...of any kind..."

995
01:31:25,400 --> 01:31:27,500
"...to"

996
01:31:28,100 --> 01:31:30,400
"Martin Pawley."

997
01:31:32,910 --> 01:31:36,070
What do you mean, you don't have any "blood kin"?

998
01:31:36,250 --> 01:31:39,880
-Debbie is your blood kin! -Not no more, she ain't!

999
01:31:40,280 --> 01:31:42,620
Well, you can keep your will!

1000
01:31:42,790 --> 01:31:44,580
I don't want any of your property!

1001
01:31:45,220 --> 01:31:46,600
Besides, I ain't forgettin'

1002
01:31:46,600 --> 01:31:48,520
you was gettin' all set to shoot her yourself.

1003
01:31:48,730 --> 01:31:50,390
What kind of man are you anyway?

1004
01:31:50,390 --> 01:31:51,680
She's been livin' with a buck!

1005
01:31:51,900 --> 01:31:54,390
Shut your dirty mouth!

1006
01:32:00,440 --> 01:32:02,560
I hope you die!

1007
01:32:03,270 --> 01:32:05,700
That'll be the day!

1008
01:32:14,280 --> 01:32:16,120
One, two, three, four!

1009
01:33:04,870 --> 01:33:05,840
Good evening, everybody!

1010
01:33:05,840 --> 01:33:07,500
Good evening, sister, we are back.

1011
01:33:07,670 --> 01:33:09,160
-Good evening. -Good evening, where is  Charlie

1012
01:33:09,340 --> 01:33:12,290
Here he is! All curried,

1013
01:33:12,290 --> 01:33:13,660
combed and washed behind the ears.

1014
01:33:13,840 --> 01:33:16,770
Charlie, you look right handsome! I'd hardly know you.

1015
01:33:16,950 --> 01:33:20,510
Yes, ma'am. I can't hardly recognize myself.

1016
01:33:20,680 --> 01:33:23,070
Get it on, Luther!

1017
01:33:24,150 --> 01:33:26,140
-Hi, partners. -Hi, Charlie

1018
01:33:26,320 --> 01:33:28,520
How is your guita

1019
01:33:39,540 --> 01:33:41,830
-Why don't you have a drink, Reverend? -Oh, no, Nesby.

1020
01:33:42,010 --> 01:33:43,830
Not till I'm finished my clergyin'.

1021
01:33:43,830 --> 01:33:45,830
Bar's closed. Right, Sister Jorgensen?

1022
01:33:46,010 --> 01:33:48,970
-Right! -All right, let's go! Let's get it goin'!

1023
01:33:49,150 --> 01:33:51,100
Charlie

1024
01:34:00,690 --> 01:34:02,610
Go ahead.

1025
01:34:04,890 --> 01:34:06,560
Bible.

1026
01:34:09,230 --> 01:34:12,690
-Get them spurs off! -Yes, sir.

1027
01:34:15,710 --> 01:34:18,070
All right, line up inside, boys.

1028
01:34:29,020 --> 01:34:30,450
Music!

1029
01:35:09,560 --> 01:35:10,590
Hey, you don't suppose they're

1030
01:35:10,590 --> 01:35:12,390
throwin' a party for us, do you?

1031
01:35:12,560 --> 01:35:14,830
That'll be the day!

1032
01:35:20,440 --> 01:35:22,560
I'm all right.

1033
01:35:27,480 --> 01:35:30,440
Ethan, Martin! You can't come in!

1034
01:35:30,610 --> 01:35:32,040
The rangers are in there.

1035
01:35:32,040 --> 01:35:33,310
What's that got to do with us?

1036
01:35:33,480 --> 01:35:35,580
You're both posted for murder. The both of you!

1037
01:35:35,750 --> 01:35:38,310
That trader, the late Futterman...

1038
01:35:38,490 --> 01:35:41,290
The Reverend and the rangers are in there now...

1039
01:35:41,460 --> 01:35:44,220
Well, what's goin' on anyway?

1040
01:35:52,670 --> 01:35:54,510
Looks like you two will have a lot to talk about.

1041
01:35:54,510 --> 01:35:55,430
Come on, Lars.

1042
01:35:55,610 --> 01:35:59,300
-Ethan...hide in the barn! -What for?

1043
01:36:04,510 --> 01:36:07,640
Please! Look, everybody!

1044
01:36:07,850 --> 01:36:12,480
Look, Mama! Look who's here!

1045
01:36:13,060 --> 01:36:14,850
Evenin'.

1046
01:36:17,560 --> 01:36:19,980
-Is the bar open? -Ethan.

1047
01:36:20,160 --> 01:36:22,550
Any news of our little girl?

1048
01:36:22,770 --> 01:36:25,030
She's not a little girl anymore.

1049
01:36:25,200 --> 01:36:28,160
You've seen her? She's alive?

1050
01:36:28,160 --> 01:36:30,490
I've seen her and she's alive.

1051
01:36:31,310 --> 01:36:33,200
Good evening, Reverend.

1052
01:36:33,380 --> 01:36:35,540
Or should I call you "Captain"?

1053
01:36:35,710 --> 01:36:37,700
I came here for a wedding, Ethan.

1054
01:36:37,880 --> 01:36:40,250
Till that's over, "Reverend" will do.

1055
01:36:40,420 --> 01:36:43,510
-Afterwards we'll talk. -Is Marty with you?

1056
01:36:43,690 --> 01:36:45,480
Yep.

1057
01:36:46,820 --> 01:36:48,150
-Charlie, please! -Charlie!

1058
01:36:48,320 --> 01:36:49,660
Mama

1059
01:36:49,830 --> 01:36:52,820
It's good to see you back, Ethan. We'll join you.

1060
01:36:54,200 --> 01:36:56,690
But I wrote you one letter.

1061
01:36:56,830 --> 01:36:59,860
One letter in five years!

1062
01:37:00,040 --> 01:37:02,920
I read it till the paper dried up

1063
01:37:02,920 --> 01:37:04,500
and the writin' faded out.

1064
01:37:05,010 --> 01:37:08,400
It wasn't much of a letter, was it?

1065
01:37:08,580 --> 01:37:10,840
No, it wasn't.

1066
01:37:11,610 --> 01:37:14,110
Might've at least said you loved me.

1067
01:37:14,320 --> 01:37:16,380
You might've asked me to wait for you.

1068
01:37:16,380 --> 01:37:18,450
At least that'd have been somethin'.

1069
01:37:20,390 --> 01:37:22,720
But I always loved you!

1070
01:37:23,330 --> 01:37:26,630
I thought you knew that without me havin' to say it.

1071
01:37:27,430 --> 01:37:30,190
It isn't fair, Martin Pawley!

1072
01:37:30,870 --> 01:37:32,530
It isn't fair and you know it!

1073
01:37:32,700 --> 01:37:36,700
-I wish you wouldn't cry, Laurie. -Who's cryin'?

1074
01:37:42,910 --> 01:37:49,100
I reckon the best thing for me to do is to go away.

1075
01:37:50,250 --> 01:37:54,420
You do, Martin Pawley, and I'll just die!

1076
01:38:05,800 --> 01:38:10,260
I'll thank you to unhand my fiance.

1077
01:38:13,180 --> 01:38:16,810
You don't mean you're gonna be marryin' him?

1078
01:38:16,980 --> 01:38:20,400
-Charlie MacCorry? -She sure is!

1079
01:38:20,580 --> 01:38:22,640
And don't think your comin' back

1080
01:38:22,640 --> 01:38:24,410
is gonna change it either!

1081
01:38:24,590 --> 01:38:27,180
Well, now, as to that, I just don't know, Charlie.

1082
01:38:27,390 --> 01:38:29,760
We hadn't gotten around to talkin' about marriage.

1083
01:38:29,930 --> 01:38:33,280
What right have you to talk marriage to any decent woman?

1084
01:38:33,460 --> 01:38:35,450
If you're referrin' to that crazy murder charge...

1085
01:38:35,630 --> 01:38:37,860
And other things.

1086
01:38:38,030 --> 01:38:40,830
You think you're gettin' away with bein' smart

1087
01:38:41,000 --> 01:38:44,300
about the Indian wife you took.

1088
01:38:46,110 --> 01:38:48,340
I'll bet she ain't the first squaw you ever...

1089
01:38:48,510 --> 01:38:52,110
Why, you are a no good...

1090
01:38:53,280 --> 01:38:55,670
Oh, Marty, you've done it again!

1091
01:38:58,120 --> 01:39:00,320
Get out of my way!

1092
01:39:00,520 --> 01:39:02,190
Marty! Charlie! I ain't gonna have

1093
01:39:02,190 --> 01:39:03,190
no fightin' in my house.

1094
01:39:03,360 --> 01:39:06,190
Well, then we're just gonna fight outside, doggone it!

1095
01:39:06,360 --> 01:39:07,950
I ain't totin' no firearms.

1096
01:39:08,130 --> 01:39:10,120
Well, that sure ain't gonna be no problem.

1097
01:39:10,300 --> 01:39:12,390
Ma! Pa! Reverend!

1098
01:39:12,570 --> 01:39:15,700
-After you, Marty. -After you, Charlie.

1099
01:39:15,940 --> 01:39:19,860
Ma! Reverend! Pa!

1100
01:39:22,210 --> 01:39:23,970
Look, here.

1101
01:39:27,050 --> 01:39:28,880
Thank you.

1102
01:39:36,760 --> 01:39:39,820
Spit over that piece of firewood.

1103
01:39:56,710 --> 01:40:00,200
Quit that, Marty! That ain't fair!

1104
01:40:04,190 --> 01:40:07,880
Martin! Martin! Charlie!

1105
01:40:08,590 --> 01:40:12,190
-Marty, now you stop that! -Marty! Charlie!

1106
01:40:12,360 --> 01:40:14,420
Marty!

1107
01:40:15,700 --> 01:40:20,020
-Sergeant MacCorry! -Yes, sir.

1108
01:40:20,200 --> 01:40:22,800
Is this here altercation in the line of duty?

1109
01:40:23,270 --> 01:40:26,440
No, sir. It's more in the nature of a private fight.

1110
01:40:26,610 --> 01:40:29,580
All right, then, go ahead. But fight fair.

1111
01:40:29,580 --> 01:40:31,710
No biting or gouging!

1112
01:40:31,880 --> 01:40:34,250
And no kicking either!

1113
01:40:35,380 --> 01:40:37,750
Get them up! Make them fight fair!

1114
01:40:37,920 --> 01:40:39,580
Now you fight fair, Martin!

1115
01:40:39,760 --> 01:40:41,420
Wait a minute! Martin!

1116
01:40:41,590 --> 01:40:46,080
-Somebody's fiddle. -Hey, Seth!

1117
01:40:46,760 --> 01:40:49,820
No choking! No gouging!

1118
01:40:50,230 --> 01:40:53,070
Pa. Mr. Edwards, make 'em stop!

1119
01:40:53,240 --> 01:40:58,590
-Why? You started it. -Marty, watch his feet!

1120
01:40:59,140 --> 01:41:03,460
-Oh, Ethan! No! -Don't forget, you're a lady.

1121
01:41:03,650 --> 01:41:05,570
-Come on now. -Fight fair!

1122
01:41:05,750 --> 01:41:07,610
Fight fair!

1123
01:41:08,990 --> 01:41:10,820
Come on, Charlie. Get up!

1124
01:41:11,050 --> 01:41:14,110
Come on, Charlie. Get up!

1125
01:41:17,830 --> 01:41:21,350
Charlie. Come on, Charlie. Get up!

1126
01:41:21,560 --> 01:41:23,830
-Charlie. Are you all right? -Marty, get up.

1127
01:41:24,000 --> 01:41:26,160
I reckon so.

1128
01:41:26,840 --> 01:41:28,960
Now, come on. I want you boys to

1129
01:41:28,960 --> 01:41:30,170
shake hands and make friends.

1130
01:41:31,770 --> 01:41:34,630
Sorry I bit your ear, Marty.

1131
01:41:34,810 --> 01:41:38,200
It don't hurt none, Charlie.

1132
01:41:38,380 --> 01:41:40,780
Now you boys get cleaned up and

1133
01:41:40,780 --> 01:41:42,370
we'll proceed with the wedding.

1134
01:41:42,590 --> 01:41:46,510
-Where's my Bible? -There ain't gonna be no wedding.

1135
01:41:53,700 --> 01:41:58,020
Not till we get a few things cleared up around here.

1136
01:42:01,700 --> 01:42:05,130
It was a nice wedding party,

1137
01:42:05,310 --> 01:42:08,160
considering nobody got married.

1138
01:42:11,150 --> 01:42:14,140
Ethan, I gotta ask you and Martin to

1139
01:42:14,140 --> 01:42:16,040
take a ride with me down to the state capital.

1140
01:42:16,490 --> 01:42:19,840
Is this an invite to a necktie party, Reverend?

1141
01:42:20,020 --> 01:42:22,580
No, I wouldn't say that.

1142
01:42:22,760 --> 01:42:26,490
Likely you had your reasons for killin' Futterman.

1143
01:42:26,660 --> 01:42:28,760
Probably needed killin'.

1144
01:42:28,930 --> 01:42:33,430
I'm talking to you now as a ranger, not as a preacher.

1145
01:42:33,640 --> 01:42:36,400
The fact that all three of 'em was shot in the back was

1146
01:42:36,570 --> 01:42:39,700
...the only thing that raised some questions.

1147
01:42:39,880 --> 01:42:41,760
That, and...

1148
01:42:41,940 --> 01:42:45,840
a missin' gold piece that was known to have been on him

1149
01:42:46,350 --> 01:42:49,370
...just prior to his demise.

1150
01:42:50,520 --> 01:42:54,440
Ethan, I'll have to ask you for your gun.

1151
01:43:06,440 --> 01:43:09,430
Well, if it's all the same to you, Reverend...

1152
01:43:09,710 --> 01:43:11,400
...I ain't goin' to Austin!

1153
01:43:11,400 --> 01:43:12,900
You're goin' if the captain says so.

1154
01:43:13,080 --> 01:43:15,200
Stop it! Stop it!

1155
01:43:15,380 --> 01:43:17,770
I'll put both of you boys in the smokehouse to cool off.

1156
01:43:17,950 --> 01:43:20,680
Marty sit down

1157
01:43:21,880 --> 01:43:24,910
Good evening, ma'am. Captain Clayton?

1158
01:43:25,720 --> 01:43:27,090
Excuse me, ma'am.

1159
01:43:28,090 --> 01:43:31,620
-Captain Clayton, sir? -No.

1160
01:43:32,060 --> 01:43:33,760
I'm Captain Clayton.

1161
01:43:33,930 --> 01:43:36,420
-You're Captain Clayton? -Yes, I'm Captain Clayton.

1162
01:43:36,970 --> 01:43:38,800
Col. Greenhill's compliments, sir.

1163
01:43:38,970 --> 01:43:40,960
-The colonel wants to know... -Is your head cold?

1164
01:43:41,140 --> 01:43:42,900
No, sir.

1165
01:43:43,110 --> 01:43:44,990
I'm sorry, sir. I beg your pardon, ma'am.

1166
01:43:45,210 --> 01:43:46,830
All right, start at the beginning.

1167
01:43:47,010 --> 01:43:49,640
Col. Greenhill's compliments, sir.

1168
01:43:49,810 --> 01:43:51,320
Hold on, son. Who is this Col. Greenhill

1169
01:43:51,320 --> 01:43:52,180
you're talking about?

1170
01:43:52,350 --> 01:43:53,590
Why, Col. Greenhill is Col. Greenhill, sir.

1171
01:43:53,590 --> 01:43:54,840
Commanding officer of the 15th...

1172
01:43:55,020 --> 01:43:57,910
-And who are you? -I'm Lt. Greenhill, sir.

1173
01:43:58,090 --> 01:44:00,420
What is it your pa wants to know?

1174
01:44:01,020 --> 01:44:02,910
Well, go ahead.

1175
01:44:03,090 --> 01:44:05,790
My pa wants to know... Col. Greenhill wants to know...

1176
01:44:05,960 --> 01:44:09,020
-how soon you can put a company... -Turn around, sonny.

1177
01:44:09,500 --> 01:44:12,520
Yeah, he's a Yankee cavalryman.

1178
01:44:12,740 --> 01:44:15,230
Col. Greenhill wants to know how soon you could...

1179
01:44:15,370 --> 01:44:19,260
-I resent that, sir! -Just funnin', son, just funnin'.

1180
01:44:19,440 --> 01:44:21,970
How soon you could put a company of your men in the field

1181
01:44:22,140 --> 01:44:23,560
fully armed for joint-punitive action

1182
01:44:23,560 --> 01:44:24,370
against the Comanches?

1183
01:44:24,550 --> 01:44:27,040
-Joint what? -Joint-punitive action.

1184
01:44:27,180 --> 01:44:28,610
We received information about

1185
01:44:28,610 --> 01:44:31,110
a band of Comanches under a chief named Scar.

1186
01:44:31,290 --> 01:44:33,650
-What information? -That maybe he's not far from here,

1187
01:44:33,820 --> 01:44:35,160
holed up somewhere.

1188
01:44:35,160 --> 01:44:36,660
What makes you think he's not far from here?

1189
01:44:36,830 --> 01:44:38,710
One of our patrollers picked up a man...

1190
01:44:38,890 --> 01:44:41,230
...claims he was a prisoner with Scar till two days ago.

1191
01:44:41,400 --> 01:44:43,560
Talks kind of crazy, but we brought him along.

1192
01:44:43,770 --> 01:44:46,260
Says he lives here. Keeps mentioning a rocking chair.

1193
01:44:46,400 --> 01:44:48,560
Mose.

1194
01:44:50,140 --> 01:44:52,000
Mose!

1195
01:44:52,810 --> 01:44:55,070
Take his arms.

1196
01:44:56,850 --> 01:44:59,180
-Old Mose! -It's Mose!

1197
01:44:59,350 --> 01:45:02,810
Good evening, ma'am. I came for my rocking chair.

1198
01:45:02,990 --> 01:45:04,250
Bring him to the fire. Watch him!

1199
01:45:04,420 --> 01:45:06,550
-Watch him! -Get him up!

1200
01:45:07,520 --> 01:45:09,180
Get him up!

1201
01:45:09,560 --> 01:45:12,360
-Here, get him a chair. -Charlie,

1202
01:45:12,530 --> 01:45:14,690
bring him a drink!

1203
01:45:15,200 --> 01:45:17,690
Watch his head!

1204
01:45:17,830 --> 01:45:19,490
Take a drink, Mose.

1205
01:45:19,670 --> 01:45:22,190
Drink that down, Mose.

1206
01:45:25,510 --> 01:45:28,430
Mose. Scar... where is he?

1207
01:45:28,610 --> 01:45:32,100
My rocking chair. You promised me my rocking chair.

1208
01:45:32,310 --> 01:45:34,080
-Where is Scar? -Ask him about Debbie.

1209
01:45:34,250 --> 01:45:36,580
Is Debbie all right, Mose?

1210
01:45:38,020 --> 01:45:41,180
Made out I was crazy.

1211
01:45:43,590 --> 01:45:46,020
You don't think I'm crazy, do you, ma'am?

1212
01:45:46,200 --> 01:45:48,640
No, Mose, you're just sick and hurt.

1213
01:45:48,640 --> 01:45:49,720
Thank you, ma'am.

1214
01:45:49,900 --> 01:45:53,250
Mose, try and remember. You were at Scar's camp.

1215
01:45:53,570 --> 01:45:56,420
I ate dirt and chewed grass. I fooled them.

1216
01:45:56,610 --> 01:45:58,940
Where is Scar holed up?

1217
01:45:59,110 --> 01:46:01,240
I won't tell you.

1218
01:46:02,380 --> 01:46:04,140
I'll tell Marty.

1219
01:46:04,350 --> 01:46:06,770
Seven Fingers, Marty.

1220
01:46:06,980 --> 01:46:07,480
Seven fingers.

1221
01:46:07,480 --> 01:46:09,470
That's enough, Ethan. Let's get him to bed.

1222
01:46:09,650 --> 01:46:11,540
Seven Fingers?

1223
01:46:12,290 --> 01:46:14,420
Beg to report, sir... that's what he told us,

1224
01:46:14,590 --> 01:46:16,480
but there's no such place on the maps.

1225
01:46:16,730 --> 01:46:18,490
Say

1226
01:46:18,660 --> 01:46:20,540
Isn't it the Caddo name

1227
01:46:20,540 --> 01:46:22,760
for where all them canyons join under the Malapai?

1228
01:46:22,930 --> 01:46:25,630
Seven Fingers of Brazos!

1229
01:46:25,800 --> 01:46:28,790
Come on, Mama. Let's get him to his room.

1230
01:46:28,970 --> 01:46:30,960
My rocking chair?

1231
01:46:31,140 --> 01:46:33,440
We'll bring it.

1232
01:46:33,740 --> 01:46:36,010
You go tell your pa that a company of rangers...

1233
01:46:36,180 --> 01:46:38,260
...all 14 of 'em, fully armed and equipped

1234
01:46:38,260 --> 01:46:40,140
will be in the field by daylight.

1235
01:46:40,320 --> 01:46:42,680
We'll be headin' for the south end of the Malapai.

1236
01:46:42,890 --> 01:46:45,080
If he can catch up with us, all well and good!

1237
01:46:45,250 --> 01:46:47,510
We can't take the field tomorrow.

1238
01:46:47,510 --> 01:46:49,280
For your own protection.

1239
01:46:49,460 --> 01:46:53,820
Sonny. Out yonder is a pack of murderers...

1240
01:46:54,000 --> 01:46:57,120
...complete with Texican scalps and a white-girl captive!

1241
01:46:57,300 --> 01:47:00,130
If you want to protect us, just keep out of our way.

1242
01:47:00,300 --> 01:47:02,460
Now you skedaddle back to your pa!

1243
01:47:02,640 --> 01:47:04,950
Ethan... You and Martin are hereby appointed

1244
01:47:04,950 --> 01:47:07,270
civilian scouts. Without pay.

1245
01:47:07,440 --> 01:47:09,670
Take the boys and get back to

1246
01:47:09,670 --> 01:47:11,900
headquarters and pick up my company.

1247
01:47:14,480 --> 01:47:16,210
Martin?

1248
01:47:21,520 --> 01:47:24,410
You're not going! Not this time.

1249
01:47:25,030 --> 01:47:27,660
-Are you crazy? -It's too late.

1250
01:47:27,830 --> 01:47:29,660
She is a woman grown now.

1251
01:47:29,830 --> 01:47:32,490
I gotta go, Laurie. I gotta fetch her home.

1252
01:47:32,670 --> 01:47:34,300
Fetch what home?

1253
01:47:34,470 --> 01:47:36,000
The leavings of Comanche bucks sold time

1254
01:47:36,000 --> 01:47:37,360
and again to the highest bidder with...

1255
01:47:37,540 --> 01:47:39,630
Laurie, shut your mouth!

1256
01:47:39,810 --> 01:47:42,200
Do you know what Ethan will do if he has a chance?

1257
01:47:42,380 --> 01:47:45,010
He'll put a bullet in her brain!

1258
01:47:45,210 --> 01:47:47,710
I tell you, Martha would want him to!

1259
01:47:47,850 --> 01:47:50,180
Only if I'm dead!

1260
01:48:38,230 --> 01:48:41,120
We can get within 200 yards of them.

1261
01:48:41,300 --> 01:48:44,300
There's a hub back off to the left.

1262
01:48:44,940 --> 01:48:47,030
How many, you figure?

1263
01:48:47,210 --> 01:48:49,540
About a dozen each.

1264
01:48:49,710 --> 01:48:52,200
Enough to go around.

1265
01:48:55,780 --> 01:48:59,020
See you leter

1266
01:49:00,090 --> 01:49:03,620
Well, we found 'em!

1267
01:49:03,790 --> 01:49:05,160
Now, men...

1268
01:49:05,330 --> 01:49:06,680
...the state of Texas

1269
01:49:06,680 --> 01:49:10,720
is paying you 12 Yankee dollars a month.

1270
01:49:10,900 --> 01:49:12,920
Now is your chance to earn it!

1271
01:49:13,270 --> 01:49:15,100
Tighten up your cinches.

1272
01:49:15,100 --> 01:49:16,930
We'll go chargin' in about sunup.

1273
01:49:17,110 --> 01:49:20,600
-Now make sure that... -Just a minute, Reverend!

1274
01:49:26,150 --> 01:49:28,810
If we go charging in, they'll kill her! And you know it.

1275
01:49:28,980 --> 01:49:31,820
-That's what I'm countin' on. -I know you are.

1276
01:49:31,990 --> 01:49:34,000
Well, it ain't gonna be that way! She's alive

1277
01:49:34,010 --> 01:49:35,010
and she's gonna stay alive!

1278
01:49:35,190 --> 01:49:37,730
Living with Comanches ain't bein' alive.

1279
01:49:37,740 --> 01:49:39,060
It's better she's alive and livin' with

1280
01:49:39,060 --> 01:49:39,850
Comanches than her brains bashed out!

1281
01:49:40,060 --> 01:49:44,420
Now, son, I know this is a bitter thing to say...

1282
01:49:44,600 --> 01:49:47,130
-but there's more at stake here than your sister. -There sure is.

1283
01:49:47,300 --> 01:49:49,030
I'm gonna tell you somethin'.

1284
01:49:49,200 --> 01:49:52,630
I didn't mean to speak of it, but I'm gonna tell you now.

1285
01:49:52,810 --> 01:49:56,270
You remember that scalp strung on Scar's lance?

1286
01:49:56,450 --> 01:49:57,640
-Long and wavy? -Yeah, I saw it.

1287
01:49:57,810 --> 01:50:00,040
And don't try to tell me it was Aunt Martha's or Lucy's!

1288
01:50:00,220 --> 01:50:02,340
It was your mother's.

1289
01:50:06,320 --> 01:50:08,710
-Come on, son. -That don't change it.

1290
01:50:08,890 --> 01:50:11,190
That don't change nothing!

1291
01:50:13,360 --> 01:50:15,030
Give me a chance to sneak in and get her out,

1292
01:50:15,030 --> 01:50:16,700
before you come chargin' in.

1293
01:50:16,870 --> 01:50:18,120
What if you get caught?

1294
01:50:18,120 --> 01:50:19,490
That don't tell them nothin', does it?

1295
01:50:19,670 --> 01:50:21,660
I said no!

1296
01:50:22,200 --> 01:50:24,470
You go right ahead, son.

1297
01:50:24,640 --> 01:50:28,000
But at the first sign of an alarm, we're comin' in.

1298
01:50:28,540 --> 01:50:31,060
We ain't gonna have no time to pick and

1299
01:50:31,060 --> 01:50:32,740
choose our targets when we do!

1300
01:50:35,220 --> 01:50:37,170
It's your funeral.

1301
01:51:43,120 --> 01:51:45,750
Captain Clayton! Captain!

1302
01:51:46,090 --> 01:51:49,980
-Captain Clayton! -What the Sam hill...?

1303
01:51:52,330 --> 01:51:56,150
-Captain Clayton, sir. -Go ahead!

1304
01:51:56,330 --> 01:51:59,490
Why don't you have your bugler blow the charge too?

1305
01:51:59,700 --> 01:52:01,730
-Sir? -Oh, never mind.

1306
01:52:01,900 --> 01:52:03,830
Does your pa know you're out here?

1307
01:52:03,830 --> 01:52:06,640
Yes, sir. The troops are 10 miles back.

1308
01:52:06,810 --> 01:52:08,350
The colonel sent me to find you.

1309
01:52:08,360 --> 01:52:10,070
You found me. Good work, Son.

1310
01:52:10,250 --> 01:52:11,400
You found me. Good work and goodbye.

1311
01:52:11,400 --> 01:52:13,270
Is there anything I can do, sir?

1312
01:52:13,450 --> 01:52:15,970
God forbid. You just go back

1313
01:52:15,970 --> 01:52:17,580
and tell your pa where we are

1314
01:52:17,750 --> 01:52:21,020
-and where he is. -But he knows that, sir.

1315
01:52:21,220 --> 01:52:24,920
Can't I stay? Please?

1316
01:52:25,230 --> 01:52:28,120
Oh, all right. But you watch me, boy.

1317
01:52:28,300 --> 01:52:31,170
I'm the hard case you're up against out here,

1318
01:52:31,170 --> 01:52:32,320
not them childish savages.

1319
01:52:32,500 --> 01:52:34,710
If you don't hear my first holler...

1320
01:52:34,710 --> 01:52:36,320
you better read my mind...

1321
01:52:36,510 --> 01:52:38,720
...'cause I don't aim to raise no two hollers

1322
01:52:38,720 --> 01:52:40,200
on any subject at hand!

1323
01:52:40,380 --> 01:52:42,710
-Yes, sir. -Boy...

1324
01:52:42,880 --> 01:52:46,740
-watch that knife! -Sorry, sir.

1325
01:53:06,200 --> 01:53:07,760
Halt!

1326
01:53:09,340 --> 01:53:10,960
Mount!

1327
01:53:15,010 --> 01:53:18,780
Mount! Mount!

1328
01:53:44,670 --> 01:53:46,330
Debbie.

1329
01:53:46,810 --> 01:53:48,500
Debbie.

1330
01:53:50,510 --> 01:53:52,650
Debbie. Don't say anything! Debbie.

1331
01:53:52,660 --> 01:53:54,370
It's your brother Marty! Debbie.

1332
01:53:54,550 --> 01:53:55,950
I'm gonna take you away.

1333
01:53:55,950 --> 01:53:57,540
I'm gonna get you out of here, Debbie.

1334
01:53:57,720 --> 01:54:01,420
Yes, Marty! Yes, Marty!

1335
01:54:08,960 --> 01:54:11,890
Brethren, let us go amongst them!

1336
01:54:12,100 --> 01:54:14,090
Trumpeter

1337
01:54:34,490 --> 01:54:35,850
Get in

1338
01:54:51,440 --> 01:54:54,270
Charlie, Nesby, run off that pony herd...

1339
01:54:54,440 --> 01:54:56,640
-Boy, you watch out for that knife! -Yes, sir.

1340
01:54:56,810 --> 01:54:58,640
Let's go!

1341
01:55:31,150 --> 01:55:34,670
No, Ethan!

1342
01:55:35,620 --> 01:55:37,610
No, Ethan!

1343
01:55:52,300 --> 01:55:54,130
Debbie!

1344
01:55:59,310 --> 01:56:01,800
No, Ethan!

1345
01:56:13,560 --> 01:56:15,940
Let's go home, Debbie.

1346
01:56:24,600 --> 01:56:27,560
-Does that hurt, Reverend? -Shut up!

1347
01:56:33,410 --> 01:56:35,170
Come on

1348
01:56:41,780 --> 01:56:44,710
Good work, Captain! Good work, Son.

1349
01:56:44,890 --> 01:56:46,750
You wounded?

1350
01:56:47,120 --> 01:56:50,850
-A bullet? An arrow? -No!

